this title|Erotica (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Erotica\n| cover      = Madonna Erotica Single.png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n| album      = [[Erotica (Madonna album)|Erotica]]\n| B-side     = \"Erotica\" (Instrumental)\n| released   = September 29, 1992\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Gramophone record|7\"]]|[[12-inch single|12\"]]|[[Cassette single|cassette]]|[[CD single|CD]]}}\n| recorded   = January 15\u201316, 1992; (demo)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faqs.org/copyright/impressive-instant-i-deserve-it-nobodys-perfect-paradise-i/ |title=Impressive instant ; I deserve it ; Nobody's perfect ; Paradise, I will always have you |publisher=Faqs.org |accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref><br>{{small|(Manhattan, New York)}}<br>June 8, 1992;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KIfrupI2_qsC&pg=PA99&lpg=PA99&dq=erotica%20madonna%20june%208,%201992&source=bl&ots=bQP0crwcd2&sig=G9TZjpa2hIbqQuBpf1X5X8JbvUU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CFAQ6AEwCWoVChMIv-_xpYf7xwIVAgySCh1nqgTM#v=onepage&q=erotica%20madonna%20june%208,%201992&f=false|title=Console Confessions: The Great Music Producers in Their Own Words|first=Anthony|last=Savona|date=1 January 2005|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|accessdate=6 October 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref><br>Sound Works Studio<br>{{small|([[Astoria, New York]])}}\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Trip hop]]|[[new jack swing]]|[[dance music|dance]]}}\n| length     = 5:20\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Maverick Records|Maverick]]|[[Sire Records|Sire]]|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]|[[Shep Pettibone]]|Anthony Shimkin}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Madonna|Shep Pettibone}}\n| prev_title = [[This Used to Be My Playground]]\n| prev_year  = 1992\n| next_title = [[Deeper and Deeper]]\n| next_year  = 1992\n}}\n\n\"'''Erotica'''\" is a song by American singer and songwriter [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]. It is the title track from her fifth [[studio album]] ''[[Erotica (Madonna album)|Erotica]]'' (1992), and was released as the album's [[lead single]] on September 29, 1992 by [[Maverick Records]]. It was later included on her greatest hits albums ''[[GHV2]]'' (2001) and ''[[Celebration (Madonna album)|Celebration]]'' (2009). The song was written by Madonna, [[Shep Pettibone]] and Anthony Shimkin, while production was handled by the singer and Pettibone. Musically, \"Erotica\" contains [[spoken word]] vocals, and is an ode to [[Sadomasochism|S&M]], with Madonna using a pseudonym called \"Dita\". She invites her lover to be passive while making love to her and leads him to explore boundaries between pain and pleasure.\n\nThe song debuted at number 13 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming one of the highest debuts on the chart history at the time, eventually peaking at number three. Additionally, it became a success on the [[Hot Dance Club Play]] chart, reaching the top position. \"Erotica\" also found commercial success internationally, peaking in the Top 10 in several countries including Denmark, Finland, New Zealand, Norway, Portugal, Sweden and the United Kingdom. In Italy and Greece it peaked at number one.\n\nThe accompanying [[music video]] for the song was directed by fashion photographer [[Fabien Baron]], and features Madonna dressed as a masked [[dominatrix]] interspersed with footage of the making of the singer's ''[[Sex (book)|Sex]]'' book, with cameos by celebrities such as [[Naomi Campbell]] and [[Big Daddy Kane]]. The video was highly controversial, being aired by [[MTV]] a total of three times, all of these after the [[Watershed (television)|10pm watershed]], before being completely banned. Madonna performed \"Erotica\" on three of her concert tours, the first being on [[The Girlie Show World Tour]] (1993), the [[Confessions Tour]] (2006) and most recently on [[The MDNA Tour]] (2012). The song has also been covered and parodied by several artists.\n\n==Background and development==\n[[File:EroticaGirlieShowUnderGround sh.jpg|thumb|upright|Madonna, dressed as a [[dominatrix]], performs \"Erotica\" as the opening song of 1993's [[The Girlie Show World Tour]].]]\nIn 1992, Madonna founded her own multi-media entertainment company, [[Maverick (entertainment company)|Maverick]], consisting of a record company ([[Maverick Records]]), a film production company ([[Maverick Films]]), and associated music publishing, television broadcasting, book publishing and merchandising divisions.<ref name=\"maverick\">{{cite news|first=Stephen |last=Holden |authorlink=Stephen Holden|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/04/20/arts/madonna-makes-a-60-million-deal.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Madonna Makes a $60&nbsp;Million Deal|accessdate=July 25, 2015|date=April 20, 1992}}</ref> The first two projects from the venture were her fifth studio album, ''Erotica'', and a coffee table book of photographs featuring Madonna, entitled ''[[Sex (book)|Sex]]''.<ref name=\"maverick\"/> For the album, Madonna primarily collaborated with producer [[Shep Pettibone]].  Pettibone first began working with Madonna during the 1980s, providing remixes for several of her singles.<ref name=SlantEro>{{cite web|last1=Cinequemani|first1=Sal|title=Madonna: Erotica Album Review|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/madonna-erotica|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=February 24, 2007|accessdate=July 25, 2015}}</ref> Alongside Pettibone, Madonna enlisted help from producer Andr\u00e9 Betts, who previously co-produced \"[[Justify My Love]]\" for ''The Immaculate Collection''.<ref name=SlantEro/> Madonna said that she was interested to work with Pettibone and Betts due to their ability to remain plugged into the dance underground, \"They come from opposite ends of the spectrum in terms of their music style and approach to music, but they're both connected to the street and they're still young and hungry\".<ref name=\"andre\">{{cite journal|last=Flick|first=Larry|title=The Man Behind Madonna's 'Erotica'|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KRAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA22|journal=Billboard|location=New York|issn=0006-2510|date=November 28, 1992|accessdate=July 25, 2015|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Pettibone in an article \"Erotica Diaries\" published on Madonna's ''Icon'' magazine, he produced a tape with four songs, for Madonna to listen to, before he traveled to Chicago, where she was filming ''[[A League of Their Own]]''. She listened to the songs and liked all of them.<ref name=\"eroticadiaries\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sheppettibone.com/sp_erotica_diaries.htm |title=Erotica Diaries&nbsp;\u2014 Written by Shep Pettibone |last=Pettibone |first=Shep |authorlink=Shep Pettibone |publisher=ShepPettibone.com |accessdate=July 25, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830193214/http://www.sheppettibone.com/sp_erotica_diaries.htm |archivedate=August 30, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After filming was complete, Madonna met Pettibone in New York City to start working together in November 1991. Their schedule was sporadic in the beginning. They were in the studio for a week and then she would work with [[Steven Meisel]] on ''Sex'', for two weeks. Occasionally, Madonna also would meet Andr\u00e9 Betts.<ref name=\"eroticadiaries\"/>  The first batch of songs Madonna and Pettibone worked on were \"Erotica\", \"[[Deeper and Deeper]]\", \"[[Rain (Madonna song)|Rain]]\" and \"Thief of Hearts\"; she would write the lyrics as Pettibone worked on the music.<ref name=\"eroticadiaries\"/> Pettibone recalled that the singer preferred to be in control of the writing process because \"her songs are her stories. They're the things she wants to say\".<ref name=eroticadiaries /> While they were mixing a song called \"Erotic\", which was released as promotional single on her ''Sex'' book, Pettibone recalled:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"You have all these great stories in the book,\" I told her, \"Why don't you use them in the song?\" I knew that Madonna was developing a 1930s dominatrix look for ''Erotica'', but I didn't realize how far she was willing to go before I saw ''Sex''. It contained stories authored by her mysteriously dark alter [ego], Dita. Madonna took the book and walked out of the room and didn't come back until about half an hour later. Suddenly she was on the mic, speaking in this very dry voice. \"My name is Dita,\" she said, \"and I'll be your mistress tonight.\" I knew that the original \"Erotica\" would never be the same again, and it wasn't. The chorus and bridge were changed entirely and the whole psyche of the song became sexier, more to the point. It seemed as if Dita brought out the best in her, actually serving as a vehicle for the dangerous territory she was traveling. Actually, it was the same name Madonna used when she'd stay in hotels around the world. Not anymore.<ref name=eroticadiaries />\n</blockquote>\n==Composition==\n{{listen\n|pos=left\n | filename     = Madonna - Erotica.ogg\n | title        = \"Erotica\"\n | description  = \"Erotica\" was described as \"an ode to [[Sadomasochism|S&M]]\", while Madonna plays her pseudonym \"Dita\" in the song, with \"aggressive lyrics\".\n | format       = [[Ogg]]\n}}\n\"Erotica\" was written by Madonna, [[Shep Pettibone]], Anthony Shimkin, while produced by Madonna and Pettibone.<ref name=\"liner\">{{Cite AV media notes|others=Madonna|title=[[Erotica (Madonna album)|Erotica]]|year=1992|type=Liner notes|publisher=Maverick Records|id=9362-45031-2}}</ref> The track continued Madonna's exploration of potent [[spoken-word]] vocals, which she had previously introduced in \"Justify My Love\".<ref name=SlantEro /> The song contains a [[Sampling (music)|sample]] of  [[Kool and the Gang]]'s \"[[Jungle Boogie]]\".<ref name=liner />\nIt also samples \"El Yom 'Ulliqa 'Ala Khashaba,  by Lebanese singer [[Fairuz]]. This sample caused controversy after Fairuz claimed her vocals had been used without her consent, and said the lyrics \"He was crucified today\", which are sung in Arabic, are taken from a religious song that is traditionally heard during [[Good Friday]] services.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Grein|first=Pau|date=March 6, 1993|title=Madonna, MJ Club-Conscious: Chicago Vibe-rates|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rw8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA29|journal=Billboard|issn=0006-2510|location=New York|accessdate=July 13, 2012|ref=harv}}</ref> This led to a lawsuit that was [[Settlement (litigation)|settled out of court]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Fairuz's voice; opium for Arabs or symbol of peace?|url=http://www.sahafi.jo/arc/art1.php?id=0845c117594f5a492d54c98d9f451086eb89308d|publisher=Sahafi.jo|accessdate=August 1, 2015|date=January 3, 2011}}</ref> According to the sheet music published by Musicnotes.com, the song is set in [[Time signature|common time]] with a moderate [[tempo]] of 120 [[beats per minute]]. It is composed in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[F-sharp minor]] with Madonna's vocals spanning from [[F (musical note)|F#<sup>3</sup>]] to [[A (musical note)|A<sup>4</sup>]].<ref name=\"musicnotes1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0085001 |title=Madonna Ciccone: Erotica |publisher=Musicnotes.com. [[Alfred Publishing]] |accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref>\nAlso present throughout the song are [[maraca]]s and  \"shimmering horn riffs\".<ref name=RSErotica>{{cite web|last1=Berger|first1=Arion|title=Madonna - Erotica|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/erotica-19921126|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=August 1, 2015|date=November 26, 1992}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Sal Cinquemani from ''[[Slant Magazine]]'', the song is \"an ode to [[Sadomasochism|S&M]]\".<ref name=SlantEro /> It begins with a \"put-a-record-on scratchiness\" sound that mimics a record player.<ref name=Slant100>{{cite web|title=The 100 Best Singles of the 1990s|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/best-singles-of-the-1990s/247/page_7/P7|work=Slant Magazine|accessdate=July 25, 2015|date=January 9, 2011}}</ref> Following this, Madonna says, \"My name is Dita\", as she invites her lover to be passive and childlike while she makes love to him and leads him to explore boundaries between pain and pleasure.<ref name=\"maverick\"/> Madonna's use of the [[pseudonym]] \"Mistress Dita\" in the song, as well as in  ''Sex'', is a homage to [[Dita Parlo]], a German actress who was known for \"not caring what people thought\".<ref name=Guilbert>{{harvnb|Guilbert|2002|p=122}}</ref> The song has suggestive lyrics, such as \"Will you let yourself go wild/Let my mouth go where it wants to\".<ref>{{harvnb|Lenig|2010|p=144}}</ref> ''Slant Magazine'' described these lyrics as \"taunting, aggressive\u2014an elaborate exploration of sex, from seduction to disease\".<ref name=Slant100 /> A similar song titled \"Erotic\", was created during the ''Erotica'' album sessions exclusively to accompany the 1992 book ''Sex''. The song, a stripped-down version of \"Erotica\", includes lyrics not heard in the original track such as \"We could use the cage, I've got a lot of rope\".<ref name=Guilbert2>{{harvnb|Guilbert|2002|p=160}}</ref> Academic [[Georges Claude Guilbert]], called \"Erotic\" a \"more hardcore\" version of \"Erotica\".<ref name=Guilbert2/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[File:EroticaYouThrillMeFresno2.jpg|thumb|upright|Madonna and her dancers perform a [[remix]]ed version of \"Erotica\", during the [[Confessions Tour]] in 2006.]]\n\"Erotica\" received generally positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]]. [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] from [[Allmusic]] highlighted the song as an album standout, calling it \"some of Madonna's best and most accomplished music\".<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r58712|pure_url=yes}}|title=Erotica > Overview|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s  Arion Berger wrote: \"'Erotica' [...] promise[s] a smorgasbord of sexual experimentation, like the one portrayed in the video for 'Justify My Love'. But the sensibility of 'Erotica' is miles removed from the warm come-ons of 'Justify', which got its heat from privacy and romance [...] The Madonna of 'Erotica' is in no way interested in your dreams; she's after compliance\"; he called the song \"'[[Vogue (Madonna song)|Vogue]]' with a dirty mouth, where all the real action's on the dance floor\".<ref name=RSErotica />  [[Stephen Holden]] from ''[[The New York Times]]'', commented that the \"foggy growl\" that Madonna uses in the spoken-word sections of the song \"contrast dramatically with the shrill little-kid voice from Madonna's earliest records that she still often uses to project a bratty teen-age exuberance\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Holden|first=Stephen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/18/arts/recordings-view-selling-sex-and-oh-yes-a-record.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|title=Recordings View; Selling Sex and (Oh, Yes) a Record|work=The New York Times|date=October 18, 1992|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref> J. Randy Taraborrelli, author of ''[[Madonna: An Intimate Biography]]'', wrote that \"['Erotica'] wasn't a surprise for anyone who had been paying attention to Madonna's recent music. She had shown her hand earlier with ''[[I'm Breathless|Breathless]]'' when she sang '[[Hanky Panky (Madonna song)|Hanky Panky]]', the song about spanking [...] then there was her single 'Justify My Love' [...] 'Erotica' though, was the full-blown music exploration, an ''exhibition'', of what we were to believe was Madonna's sexual reality\".<ref>{{harvnb|Taraborrelli|2008|p=226}}</ref> Authors Allen Metz and Carol Benson, called it \"a [[Bondage (BDSM)|bondage]] update on 'Justify My Love'\".<ref>{{harvnb|Metz|Benson|1999|p=18}}</ref> Matthew Jacobs from ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', placed it at number 23 of his list \"The Definitive Ranking Of Madonna Singles\"; Jacobs wrote \"Released at the apex of Madonna's sex appeal, 'Erotica' and its accompanying title album are remarkable as a period of innovation for the singer\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jacobs|first1=Matthew|title=The Definitive Ranking Of Madonna Singles|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/22/the-definitive-ranking-of-madonna-singles_n_5078934.html|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=August 1, 2015|date=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''[[Gay Star News]]'' placed the song at number 17 on their list \"The Definitive Ranking of Madonna's Top 55 Songs\"; author Joe Morgan called it \"Daring, sexy, and unabashed\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Morgan|first1=Joe|title=The Definitive Ranking of Madonna's Top 55 Songs|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/definitive-ranking-madonnas-top-55-songs150814/|work=[[Gay Star News]]|date=August 15, 2014|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref> In 2011, ''Slant Magazine'' listed \"Erotica\" at number thirty-four on their list \"The 100 Best Singles of the 1990s\", stating that Madonna's \"throaty\" delivery throughout the song is effective in making the lyrics seem \"incredibly honest\".<ref name=Slant100 /> The magazine goes on to say the song is Madonna's \"invitation to the dance, a slithering, sinister snake rising from a gaudily ornate chalice. The beats are, by design, hypnotic\u2014at once alluring and devious. With 'Erotica', Madonna promises to get you off, but not without giving you something\".<ref name=Slant100 /> \"Erotica\" was also shortlisted for ''Slant Magazine''{{'}}s \"100 Greatest Dance Songs\".<ref>{{cite web|work=Slant Magazine|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/100-greatest-dance-songs/P8 |title=100 Greatest Dance Songs|date=January 30, 2006|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref> Writing for ''[[AfterEllen.com and TheBacklot.com|The Backlot]]'', Louis Virtel places the song at number eight on his list of \"The 100 Greatest Madonna Songs\", describing it as a \"hot, smutty grind of a dance anthem\". Virtel added that Madonna sells the double entendre of \"Erotica\" like a \"primed burlesque mistress\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Virtel|first1=Louis|title=The 100 Greatest Madonna Songs|url=http://www.thebacklot.com/the-100-greatest-madonna-songs/02/2012/5/|work=[[AfterEllen.com and TheBacklot.com|The Backlot]]|accessdate=August 1, 2015|date=February 3, 2012}}</ref> Scott Kearnan of ''[[Boston.com]]'', included the track at number 6 on his list \"30 Best Madonna Songs\"; commenting that \"no pop star of her fame has been this sexually transgressive before or since... [[Rihanna]] sings about \"[[S&M (song)|S&M]]\" like it's a song about [[My Little Pony]], but Madonna dishes on pain, pleasure, and power with the conviction of a whip crack\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kearnan|first1=Scott|title=The 30 ultimate Madonna singles|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/music/30_best_madonna_singles_ultimate_song_list/|work=[[Boston Globe]]|accessdate=August 1, 2015|date=September 9, 2013}}</ref> [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave it a more unfavorable review, describing it as \"depressingly trite \u2014 that between its frigid melody and your scary ''My name is Dita'' spoken bits, it's about as sexy as an episode of the [[Shelley Hack]]-era ''[[Charlie's Angels]]''\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Browne|first1=David|title=Erotica Review|url=http://www.ew.com/article/1992/10/23/erotica|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=August 1, 2015|date=October 23, 1992|authorlink=David Browne (journalist)}}</ref> Also negative was ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s [[Jude Rogers]], who called it \"an oddly sexless Sex-era single\", criticizing its \"synthesised sighs\"; nonetheless, she placed \"Erotica\" at number 68 on her ranking of Madonna's singles, in honor of her 60th birthday.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rogers |first1=Jude | authorlink = Jude Rogers |title=Every one of Madonna's 78 singles \u2013 ranked! |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/aug/16/every-one-of-madonnas-78-singles-ranked |work=The Guardian |accessdate=26 August 2018 |date=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\nOn October 17, 1992, \"Erotica\" debuted at number 13 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], which at the time of its release placed Madonna in a fifth place tie with [[Mariah Carey]]'s rendition of \"[[I'll Be There (The Jackson 5 song)#Mariah Carey version|I'll Be There]]\" as the highest debut for a song in the history of the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bronson|first1=Fred|title=Janet Jackson Has Done It Again!|journal=Billboard|date=September 16, 1995|page=96|volume=107|issue=37|issn=0006-2510|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6Q0EAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_summary_r&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Erotica%20Madonna&f=false|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref> The song ultimately peaked at number three on the week of October 24, 1992.<ref name=BB>{{cite web|title=Madonna: Chart History|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/308786/madonna/chart?page=3&f=379|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref> It eventually received a [[RIAA certification|gold certification]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) on December 10, 1992, for shipments of 500,000 copies.<ref name=riaa/> \"Erotica\" also has the highest debut in the history of the [[Hot 100 Airplay (Radio Songs)|Hot 100 Airplay]] chart, entering at number two, on October 17, 1992.<ref name=Hot100>{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Ask Billboard: Shakira's Biggest Hot 100 Hits|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/5930276/ask-billboard-shakiras-biggest-hot-100-hits?page=0%2C1|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 1, 2015|date=March 7, 2014}}</ref> In Canada, the song peaked at number 13 of the [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'' Top Singles]] chart, the week of November 21, 1992.<ref name=RPM>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.1868&volume=56&issue=21&issue_dt=November%2021%201992&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top Singles - Volume 56, No. 14, October 03 1992|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=August 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923004511/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.1868&volume=56&issue=21&issue_dt=November%2021%201992&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archive-date=September 23, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In Australia, \"Erotica\" debuted at number 16 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]], the week of October 25, 1992. It reached a peak of number four, having spent a total of eleven weeks on the chart.<ref name=Aus>{{cite web|title=Australian-charts.com \u2013 Madonna \u2013 Erotica |url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Madonna&titel=Erotica&cat=s |publisher=[[ARIA Charts|ARIA]] |accessdate=August 1, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150831213811/http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Madonna&titel=Erotica&cat=s |archivedate=August 31, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, \"Erotica\" debuted at number 11 in the [[UK Singles Chart]], the week of October 17, 1992, ultimately peaking at the third position. The song was present a total of 9 weeks on the chart.<ref name=UK>{{cite web|title=Madonna: Artist Chart History|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/erotica/|publisher=[[UK Singles Chart]]|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref> As of 2008, the single has sold over 270,800 copies in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jones |first1=Alan |title=The immaculate guide to 50 years of Madonna |url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=22&storycode=1035210 |work=[[Music Week]] |accessdate=August 1, 2015 |date=August 19, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821231048/http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=22&storycode=1035210 |archivedate=August 21, 2008 }}</ref> In France, the song debuted at number 30 of the [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP Single Charts]], on the week of November 11, 1992, before peaking at number 23.<ref name=Fra>{{cite web|title=Lescharts.com \u2013 Madonna \u2013 Erotica |url=http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Madonna&titel=Erotica&cat=s |publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|Les classement single]] |accessdate=July 25, 2015 |language=French |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111115030340/http://lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Madonna&titel=Erotica&cat=s |archivedate=November 15, 2011 }}</ref> The track was also commercially successful in other places such as Spain, Ireland and Sweden, where it managed to peak within the top five of the charts.<ref name=\"spain\">{{Cite book|title=S\u00f3lo \u00e9xitos: a\u00f1o a a\u00f1o, 1959\u20132002|last=Salaverri|first=Fernando|date=September 2005|publisher=Fundaci\u00f3n Autor-SGAE|isbn=84-8048-639-2|edition=1st|location=Spain}}<!--|accessdate=2010-07-13--></ref><ref name=Ire>{{cite web|title=The Irish Charts \u2013 Search Results \u2013 Erotica |url=http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |publisher=[[Irish Singles Chart]] |accessdate=August 1, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090602061251/http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |archivedate=June 2, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=Utra>{{cite web|title=Ultratop.be \u2013 Madonna \u2013 Erotica|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/song/9db/Madonna-Erotica|publisher=[[Ultratop|Ultratop 50]]|accessdate=August 1, 2015|language=Dutch}}</ref> \"Erotica\" also reached the top spot of the [[European Hot 100 Singles]], the week of October 23, 1992.<ref name=Euro>{{cite journal|last1=Billboard Communications|title=Hits of the World: Eurochart Hot 100|journal=Billboard|date=November 14, 1992|page=46|volume=104|issue=46|issn=0006-2510|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QhAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA46|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| image1 = Isabella Rossellini - at the 2005 Torino Film Festival (cropped).jpg\n| width1 = 132\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = NaomiCampbell.jpg\n| width2 = 157\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = Models [[Isabella Rossellini]] (''left'') and [[Naomi Campbell]] (''right'') are among the celebrities that appeared in the \"Erotica\" music video alongside Madonna.\n}}\nThe [[music video]] for \"Erotica\" was directed by fashion photographer [[Fabien Baron]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsroom.mtv.com/2010/10/20/madonna-erotica/|title=Madonna Gets Kinky With Erotica: Wake-Up Video|first=Kyle|last=Anderson|date=October 20, 2010|publisher=[[MTV]]|accessdate=August 1, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120711174302/http://newsroom.mtv.com/2010/10/20/madonna-erotica/|archivedate=July 11, 2012}}</ref> The video intercalates scenes of Madonna, dressed as a masked dominatrix with a [[gold tooth]], with actual footage of the making of her ''Sex'' book; in these scenes Madonna is seen sitting [[Toplessness|topless]] in the lap of an older man, kissing model [[Naomi Campbell]], wearing [[BDSM]] gear and riding a bicycle in the nude.<ref name=EWVideo /> The video also counts with [[Cameo appearance|cameos]] by celebrities such as [[Isabella Rossellini]], [[Princess Tatiana von F\u00fcrstenberg]], [[Helmut Berger]] and [[Big Daddy Kane]].<ref name=\"CarynNYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/25/books/the-empress-has-no-clothes.html?scp=4&sq=madonna%20sex&st=cse|title=The Empress Has No Clothes|date=October 25, 1992|accessdate=August 1, 2015|first=James|last=Caryn|work=[[The New York Times]]|pages=1\u20133}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Muro |first1=Matt |title=Madonna\u2019s Top 11 Controversies (And How They Helped Her Succeed Commercially) |url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2012-03-30/madonna-top-controversies/ |publisher=[[VH1]] |accessdate=August 1, 2015 |date=March 30, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712025608/http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2012-03-30/madonna-top-controversies/ |archivedate=July 12, 2015 }}</ref> Shooting for the footage of Madonna singing the song, took place on August 22, 1992 at [[The Kitchen]] in New York City while shootings for ''Sex'' took place at [[Hotel Chelsea]] and Times Square's all-male burlesque [[Gaiety Theatre, New York (male burlesque)|Gaiety Theatre]].<ref name=\"Chelsea\">{{cite web |url=http://www.chelseahotelblog.com/living_with_legends_the_h/rock_roll/|title=You Can Tell This Book By Its Cover|accessdate=August 1, 2015|work=[[Hotel Chelsea]]}}</ref> In order to imitate the look of old [[home movies]] and [[stag film]]s, the entire video was shot with super 8&nbsp;mm film.<ref name=Harv1>{{harvnb|Metz|Benson|1999|p=17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=New Processing for Black & White Film|url=http://www.pro8mm.com/blog/new-black-and-white-processing-at-pro8mm-lends-to-a-new-school-of-thought-about-old-school-black-and-white-film/|publisher=Pro8mm.com|accessdate=August 1, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529084309/http://www.pro8mm.com/blog/new-black-and-white-processing-at-pro8mm-lends-to-a-new-school-of-thought-about-old-school-black-and-white-film/|archivedate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> The video had its world premiere on [[MTV]], on October 2, 1992.<ref name=Philly>{{cite web|last1=Bibisi|first1=Susan|title=A Tempest In A Sexpot|url=http://articles.philly.com/1992-10-20/news/26000068_1_blond-ambition-tour-videos-booby-prize|publisher=[[Philadelphia Media Network]]|accessdate=August 1, 2015|date=October 20, 1992}}</ref> Upon its release, it was met with controversy; Susan Bibisi, from ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'', called it a \"virtual advertisement\" for ''Sex''\".<ref name=Philly /> ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' had previously reported that Madonna herself had initiated the mayhem surrounding the video by walking bare breasted at designer [[Jean Paul Gaultier]]'s fashion show and posing nude in ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hart|first=Mary|title=Will She Do It?|authorlink=Mary Hart|work=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|date=October 14, 1992}}</ref> Richard Harrington from ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote:\n<blockquote>\n\"In the video, Madonna becomes [[Dita Parlo]], a masked, gold-toothed dominatrix from an indeterminate age, ready to help us cross the street at the corner of Pleasure and Pain [...] assuming different dominatrix roles and investigating assorted bondage scenarios before finishing up with some nude hitchhiking on a street remarkable free of pile-ups. Shot in grainy black and white, 'Erotica' has the feel of a stag film, though its quick cuts keep the viewer from seeing all that much\".<ref name=Harv1/>\n</blockquote>\nAfter its release, it was aired by MTV a total of three times, all of these after the [[Watershed (television)|10pm watershed]], due to its highly charged sexual content, before being permanently banned; this made it Madonna's second video to be banned from airing by the channel, after \"Justify My Love\" in 1990.<ref name=Philly /><ref>{{cite web|last1=The Hollywood Reporter|title=Too Hot For MTV: 10 Music Videos That Got Banned|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/tv-film/1196246/too-hot-for-mtv-10-music-videos-that-got-banned|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 1, 2015|date=December 22, 2010}}</ref> MTV spokeswoman Linda Alexander said, \"The themes of the video are clearly aimed at a more adult audience. It is not appropriate for a general viewing audience\".<ref name=Philly /> Madonna herself said she understood the channel's ban on the video; \"MTV plays to a huge audience and a lot of them are children, and a lot of themes I'm exploring in my videos aren't meant for children, so I understand that they say I can't show it [...] I accept it\".<ref>{{harvnb|Taraborrelli|2008|p=227}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s [[Anthony DeCurtis]] said that \"This is pretty much normal Madonna fare, [...] But how much longer can you continue mining sexuality? In checking off your list of taboos, how far can you take them? At what point does it just stop being interesting?\".<ref name=Philly /> Similarly, David Browne from ''Entertainment Weekly'', asked \"Haven\u2019t we seen most of this stuff before? Can we be bored with the subject matter already? [...] no emotion is attached to the mechanics of these acts, so it\u2019s difficult to identify with or care about the characters\".<ref name=EWVideo>{{cite web|last1=Browne|first1=David|title=Erotica (music video)|url=http://www.ew.com/article/1992/10/23/erotica-music-video|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=August 1, 2015|date=October 23, 1992}}</ref> The video was nominated for the 1993 Billie Awards in four categories: Consumer print, trade print (music) and consumer print (retail), the most for a single entry.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Newman|first1=Melinda|title=Billie Awards|journal=Billboard|date=March 6, 1993|pages=65|volume=105|issue=10|issn= 0006-2510|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rw8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA65&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Madonna%20Billie&f=false|accessdate=August 1, 2015|authorlink=HitFix#Melinda Newman}}</ref> It also was ranked at number 16 on [[VH1]]'s \"50 Sexiest Video Moments\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=65466 |title=Ep. 066 &#124; 50 Sexiest Video Moments (50-1) (2 Hours) &#124; Episode Summary, Highlights, and Recaps |publisher=VH1|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref> The video was made commercially available in 2009, when it was included, albeit in a censored version, on Madonna's ''[[Celebration: The Video Collection]]'' compilation; it had previously been excluded from 1999's ''[[The Video Collection 93:99]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.madonna.com/news/title/celebration--track-listing-for-cd--dvd-announced|title='Celebration' - Track Listing for CD & DVD Announced|date=August 25, 2009|publisher=Icon: Official Madonna website. Madonna.com|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\n[[File:MDNACN4120 (7823643740) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Madonna performing \"The Erotic Candy Shop\" during [[The MDNA Tour]] on 2012.]]\nMadonna first performed \"Erotica\" as the opening number of her [[List of Madonna concert tours|fourth concert tour]], [[The Girlie Show World Tour]] of 1993. The show opened with a topless [[pole dancer]] sliding down a pole dangling high above the stage.<ref name=Lenig>{{harvnb|Lenig|2010|p=145}}</ref> As the dancer disappears into the stage, Madonna emerges dressed as a short-haired dominatrix, wearing a [[domino mask]], [[sequin]]ed black [[hot pants]] and bra paired with knee-high boots and brandishing a [[Crop (implement)|riding crop]].<ref>{{harvnb|Borzillo-Vrenna|2008|p=55}}</ref> She performed the song while rubbing the crop between her legs; as she performed, her dancers posed and danced suggestively around her.<ref name=Lenig/> On his review of the concert in [[New York City]], [[Jon Pareles]] from ''The New York Times'', felt that \"[during] the ethereal ''Put your hands all over my body'' in 'Erotica', the choreography suggests exercises rather than unbridled passion\".<ref name=\"GSNY\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/16/arts/review-pop-from-madonna-a-new-palatability-but-still-spicy.html|title=Review/Pop; From Madonna, a New Palatability but Still Spicy|last=Pareles|first=Jon|date=October 16, 1993|accessdate=August 1, 2015|work=The New York Times|authorlink=Jon Pareles}}</ref> The performance on the November 19, 1993 show at [[Sydney Cricket Ground]] was recorded and released on [[VHS]] and [[Laserdisc]] on April 26, 1994, as ''[[The Girlie Show: Live Down Under]]''.<ref>{{cite video|people=Madonna|title=[[The Girlie Show: Live Down Under]]|medium=VHS|publisher=Warner Music Vision|year=1993}}</ref>\n\nThirteen years later, Madonna performed a remixed version of the song as part of her 2006 [[Confessions Tour]]. The performance found Madonna, who was dressed in white leotard with purple stripes, designed by Jean-Paul Gaultier, and five couples dancing to the song in [[ballroom dance]] style.<ref name=CTVideo>{{cite web|url=http://dancemusic.about.com/od/reviews/fr/MadonnaConfDVD.htm|title=Madonna The Confessions Tour DVD/CD|last=Sparks|first=Jessica|date=August 1, 2007|work=[[About.com]]. The New York Times Company|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gallo|first1=Phill|title=Review: \u2018Madonna\u2019|url=https://variety.com/2006/music/markets-festivals/madonna-7-1200516053/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=August 1, 2015|date=May 22, 2006}}</ref> The song was remixed to include additional lyrics from the original demo, which were not included in the final version.<ref name=CTVideo/> On his review of the concert, ''Slant Magazine''{{'}}s Ed Gonzalez wrote that \"her performance of Stuart Price's \"You Thrill Me\" remix of \"Erotica\" is a smash: She ''[[disco]]''-fies the song but keeps its sex appeal, choreographing it to simple, Latin-infused dance maneuvers that are ecstatic\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Ed|title=Madonna (New York, NY - July 3, 2006)|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/madonna-new-york-ny-july-3-2006|work=Slant Magazine|accessdate=August 1, 2015|date=July 3, 2006}}</ref> The performance of the song at the August 15\u201316, 2006 shows in [[London]], at the [[Wembley Arena]], were recorded and included on both the CD and DVD version of Madonna's second live album, ''[[The Confessions Tour]]'', released in 2007.<ref name=CTVideo/>\n\nDuring [[The MDNA Tour]] (2012), Madonna performed \"The Erotic Candy Shop\", a [[Mashup (music)|mashup]] of \"Erotica\" and her 2008 song \"[[Candy Shop (Madonna song)|Candy Shop]]\", in a French [[Cabaret]] setting.<ref name=\"mdnavid\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Kellner|first=Shawn|title=Madonna MDNA Tour Night 1 at the United Center|url=http://www.chicagomusicmagazine.com/reviews/madonna-mdna-tour-night-1-at-the-united-center/|work=Chicago Music Magazine|date=October 2, 2012|accessdate=August 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923202651/http://www.chicagomusicmagazine.com/reviews/madonna-mdna-tour-night-1-at-the-united-center/|archive-date=September 23, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> On his review of the concert, Niv Elis from ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'' gave the performance a positive review, writing that it \"showcases Madonna at her visual best\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Elis|first1=Niv|title=MDNA Tour Review: Introducing Jihad Madonna|url=http://www.jpost.com/Arts-and-Culture/Entertainment/MDNA-Tour-Review-Introducing-Jihad-Madonna|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=June 6, 2012}}</ref> The performances at the November 19\u201320, 2012 shows in [[Miami]], at the [[American Airlines Arena]], were recorded and released in Madonna's fourth live album, ''[[MDNA World Tour (album)|MDNA World Tour]]''.<ref name=\"mdnavid\">{{cite AV media notes |title=[[MDNA World Tour (album)|MDNA World Tour]] |others=[[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] |year=2013 |type=CD, DVD, Blu-ray |publisher=[[Interscope Records]]|id=602537507054}}</ref>\n\n==Cover versions, parodies and usage in media==\n{{See also|List of cover versions of Madonna songs|List of Madonna tribute albums}}\nIn 1992, the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] sketch comedy series ''[[In Living Color]]'' spoofed the video for \"Erotica\" as \"Neurotica\".<ref name=\"nytimes2\">{{cite web|last=Degen|first=Pener|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/01/17/style/egos-ids-their-target-madonna.html|title=EGOS & IDS; Their Target: Madonna |work=The New York Times|date=January 17, 1993|accessdate=August 1, 2015}}</ref> In the sketch comedy show ''[[The Edge (Fox TV series)|The Edge]]'', also from Fox, cast member [[Julie Brown]] spoofed the ''Sex'' book as well as the \"Erotica\" music video.<ref name=\"nytimes2\"/> When comedian [[Sandra Bernhard]]'s one-woman show \"Giving Til It Hurts\" came to New York in November 1992, she did a short spoof of the song, called \"Neurotica\", about a woman who obsessively cleans her house.<ref name=\"nytimes2\"/>\n\n''[[The Village Voice]]'' columnist [[Michael Musto]] also recreated the nude hitchhiking scene from the ''Sex'' book and \"Erotica\" music video on the streets of Jersey City. The newspaper sold the posters of the photo for $5-profits went to the Community Research Initiative on AIDS in New York.<ref name=\"nytimes2\"/> Additionally, the 2000 compilation ''Virgin Voices: A Tribute To Madonna, Vol. 2'' features a cover by Razed in Black vs. Transmutator.<ref name=\"Madonna Tribute Band 2009\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/tribute-to-madonna-vol-2-mw0002373411|title=Tribute To Madonna, Vol. 2 \u2013 Madonna Tribute Band  |accessdate=April 20, 2013|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation}}</ref> American band The Ringtones covered the song for the [[tribute album]] ''Tribute to Madonna, Vol. 1'' (2011).<ref name=\"VirginOne\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/virgin-voices-a-tribute-to-madonna-vol-1-mw0000602295|title=Virgin Voices: A Tribute to Madonna, Vol. 1 \u2013 Various Artists  |author=Steve Huey|accessdate=August 1, 2015|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation}}</ref> A cover by The Khlone Orchestra was included on their 2011 album ''Material Girls - A Tribute to Madonna''.<ref name=\"Klone Records\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.amazon.com/Material-Girls-A-Tribute-Madonna/dp/B004VIJIUA|title=Amazon.com : Material Girls \u2013 A Tribute to Madonna|accessdate=August 1, 2015|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]}}</ref> The Sunset Lounge Orchestra covered the song on their album ''Madonna Cool Down Experience Part 2'', released in 2008.<ref name=\"Cool one\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.amazon.com/The-Madonna-Cool-Down-Experience/dp/B0014HVQQK/ref=sr_1_cc_1?s=aps&ie=UTF8&qid=1363991554&sr=1-1-catcorr&keywords=Madonna+Cool+Down+Experience|title=Amazon.com : Madonna Cool Down Experience Part 1|accessdate=August 1, 2015|publisher=Amazon.com}}</ref> \"Erotica\" was featured in a scene of Madonna's directorial debut ''[[Filth and Wisdom]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/first-night-filth-and-wisdom-berlin-film-festival-berlin-782018.html |title=First Night: Filth and Wisdom, Berlin Film Festival, Berlin |first=Kaleem |last=Aftab |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=2016-10-08 |date=2008-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing and formats==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;US 7\" single, Cassette single / Japanese 3\" CD single<ref name=\"Casette\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Erotica|others=Madonna|year=1992|type=US Cassette Single liner notes|publisher=Maverick Records|id=9-18782-2}}</ref>\n# \"Erotica\" <small>(Album Version)</small> \u2014 5:17\n# \"Erotica\" <small>(Instrumental)</small> \u2014 5:17\n\n;UK / European 7\" single, Cassette single <ref name=\"EuCasette\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Erotica|others=Madonna|year=1992|type=European Cassette Single liner notes|publisher=Maverick Records|id=9-18681-7}}</ref>\n# \"Erotica\" <small>(Album Edit)</small> \u2014 4:32\n# \"Erotica\" <small>(Instrumental)</small> \u2014 5:17\n\n;US CD maxi-single <ref name=\"USMaxi\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Erotica|others=Madonna|year=1992|type=US Maxi-Single liner notes|publisher=Maverick Records|id=9-40585-2}}</ref>\n# \"Erotica\" <small>(Album Edit)</small> \u2014 4:32\n# \"Erotica\" <small>(Kenlou B-Boy Mix)</small> \u2014 6:27\n# \"Erotica\" <small>(WO 12\")</small> \u2014 6:12\n# \"Erotica\" <small>(Underground Club Mix)</small> \u2014 4:57\n# \"Erotica\" <small>([[Masters At Work]] Dub)</small> \u2014 4:57\n# \"Erotica\" <small>(Jeep Beats)</small> \u2014 5:53\n# \"Erotica\" <small>(Madonna's in My Jeep Mix)</small> \u2014 5:50\n\n;UK 12\" vinyl, 12\" Picture Disc / European 12\" vinyl / CD single<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Erotica|o