hey-warned-about-sri-lanka-terrorist-group|title=Daesh says its 'fighters' behind Sri Lanka bombings|website=DailySabah}}</ref><br />Jammiyathul Millathu Ibrahim<ref name=\"TheHindu25May\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/the-inside-story-of-the-9-suicide-bombers-behind-sri-lankas-savage-easter-attacks/article27236216.ece|title=The inside story of the 9 suicide bombers behind Sri Lanka's savage Easter attacks|access-date=29 June 2019|newspaper=The Hindu|date=25 May 2019|last1=Srinivasan|first1=Meera}}</ref><br />[[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (claimed responsibility, alleged)<ref name=\"isisindependent\"/>}}\n| assailants   = <!-- or | assailant = -->\n| weapons      = [[RDX]] and [[acetone peroxide]], [[Explosive]] [[Fragmentation (weaponry)|Shrapnel]]\n| numparts     = <!-- or | numpart = -->\n| dfens        = <!-- or | dfen = -->\n| motive = Islamic extremism, retaliation for the [[Christchurch mosque shootings]]\n| inquiry      = [[Maithripala Sirisena|President Sirisena]] invoked emergency laws, providing [[Sri Lanka Police|police]] extensive powers; the president later stated that emergency laws would be confined to dealing with the current terrorism threat and would not be used to impinge freedom of expression<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/04/sri-lanka-bombings-latest-updates-190421092621543.html|title=Sri Lanka bombings: All the latest updates|website= Al jazeera |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n| coroner      = \n| accused      = \n| convicted    = \n| verdict      = \n| convictions  = \n| charges      = Nine individuals charged with supplying paraphernalia used in connection with an act of terrorism due to appear in [[Magistrate's Courts of Sri Lanka|Colombo Magistrates Court]] on 6 May 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/23/asia/sri-lanka-investigation-ntj-intl/|title=ISIS suspect gave advance warning of Sri Lanka bombings, source says|first1=James|last1=Griffiths|first2=Swati|last2=Gupta|website=CNN|date=23 April 2019|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n| litigation    = \n}}\n\n<!-- per MOS:BOLDTITLE and WP:SBE, neither the article's title nor related text appears in bold -->On 21 April 2019, [[Easter]] Sunday, three churches in [[Sri Lanka]] and three luxury hotels in the commercial capital, [[Colombo]], were targeted in a series of coordinated Islamic [[Terrorism|terrorist]] suicide bombings. Later that day, there were smaller explosions at a housing complex in [[Dematagoda]] and a guest house in [[Dehiwala]]. Two hundred and fifty-nine people were killed,<ref name=\"dailymirror20191003\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/front_page/Easter-Sunday-attacks-SC-grants-Leave-to-proceed-12-FR-Petitions/238-175526|title=Easter Sunday attacks SC grants Leave to proceed 12 FR Petitions|publisher=Daily Mirror Online|date=2019-10-03|accessdate=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref name=\"asiatimes20191209\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/12/article/sri-lanka-intel-chief-sacked-over-easter-attacks/|title=Sri Lanka intel chief sacked over Easter attacks|publisher=Asia Times|date=2019-12-09|accessdate=2019-12-17}}</ref> including at least 45 foreign nationals<ref name=\"ndtv.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/us-official-injured-in-sri-lanka-suicide-attack-dies-in-hospital-2034800|title=US Official, Injured in Sri Lanka Suicide Attack, Dies in Hospital|website=NDTV.com}}</ref> and three police officers, and at least 500 were injured.{{efn|''See''<ref name=\"nytimes-21apr2019\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/21/world/asia/sri-lanka-bombings.html|title=Blasts Targeting Christians Kill Hundreds in Sri Lanka|last= Bastians|first= Dharisha |date=21 April 2019|work=The New York Times |access-date=21 April 2019|last2= Gettleman|first2= Jeffrey|last3=Schultz|first3=Kai|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/blasts-at-two-sri-lanka-churches-during-easter-mass-news-agency-afp-2026233 |title= 156 Dead in Blasts at Two Sri Lanka Churches During Easter Mass: Report |date= 22 April 2019|website= NDTV |access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.thenational.ae/world/asia/sri-lanka-easter-bombings-live-blasts-during-church-services-in-colombo-1.851633 |title=Sri Lanka Easter bombings live: Blasts during church services in Colombo|website=The National|access-date=22 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sri-lanka-blast-idUSKCN1RX038 |title=Bombs kill more than 200 in Sri Lankan churches, hotels on Easter Sunday|date=21 April 2019 |work=Reuters|access-date=22 April 2019|first1= Ranga |last1= Sirilal|first2=Shihar|last2= Aneez}}</ref><ref name= cnn-21apr2019>{{Cite news|url= https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/21/asia/sri-lanka-explosions/ |first1= Sugam|last1= Pokharel|first2=Euan |last2= McKirdy |title= Sri Lanka blasts: At least 138 dead and more than 400 injured in multiple church and hotel explosions |date= 21 April 2019|work= CNN |access-date= 21 April 2019}}</ref>|name=numInjured}} The church bombings were carried out during [[Easter]] [[Mass (liturgy)|services]] in [[Negombo]], [[Batticaloa]] and Colombo; the hotels that were bombed were the [[Shangri-La Hotel, Colombo|Shangri-La]], [[Cinnamon Grand Hotel|Cinnamon Grand]], [[The Kingsbury|Kingsbury]] and [[Tropical Inn]].{{efn|''See''<ref name=\"bbc-21apr2019\">{{cite news |title=Sri Lanka attacks: More than 200 killed as churches and hotels targeted |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-48001720 | work = [[BBC News]] |date=21 April 2019 |accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"multiple blasts\">{{cite web |title=Sri Lanka Easter bombings: Mass casualties in churches and hotels |url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/04/multiple-blasts-hit-sri-lanka-churches-hotels-easter-sunday-190421050357452.html | publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |accessdate= 22 April 2019 |date= 21 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-20apr2019\">{{cite news |title= Sri Lanka blasts: hundreds injured in church and hotel explosions |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/21/sri-lanka-explosions-80-believed-injured-in-blasts-at-two-churches |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |accessdate=20 April 2019 |date= 21 April 2019|first1= Jason |last1= Burke|first2= Benjamin |last2= Parkin}}</ref><ref name=\"TropicalIndy\" />|name=hotels}} According to the [[State Intelligence Service (Sri Lanka)|State Intelligence Service]] a second wave of attacks was also planned but was stopped as a result of government raids.<ref name=\"DM319\">{{cite web |title=Failure of NTJ's second spate of orchestrated attacks |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/news-features/Failure-of-NTJ%E2%80%99s-second-spate-of-orchestrated-attacks/131-170414 |accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Sri Lankan government officials, all seven of the suicide bombers in the attacks were Sri Lankan citizens associated with [[National Thowheeth Jama'ath]], a local militant [[Islamism|Islamist]] group with suspected foreign ties, previously known for attacks against [[Buddhism|Buddhists]] and [[Sufism|Sufis]].<ref name=\"local militants\">{{cite news |title= The Latest: UN Security Council condemns Sri Lanka attack |url= https://www.sfchronicle.com/news/crime/article/The-Latest-Curfew-lifted-after-Sri-Lankan-13784450.php |accessdate= 22 April 2019 |work= San Francisco Chronicle |date= 22 April 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190422091123/https://www.sfchronicle.com/news/crime/article/The-Latest-Curfew-lifted-after-Sri-Lankan-13784450.php |archive-date= 22 April 2019 |url-status= dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/26/asia/sri-lanka-suicide-bomber-intl/index.html|title=Sri Lanka bombers' mentor is dead, but his memory still stokes fear|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=30 April 2019}}</ref> [[Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka)|State Minister of Defence]] [[Ruwan Wijewardene]] said in parliament on 23 April that the government believed the attack was in retaliation for [[Christchurch mosque shootings|the attack against Muslims in Christchurch]] on 15 March 2019.{{efn|''See''<ref name= AboutMotive>{{cite web |title= Bombings were response to Christchurch shooting \u2013 State Minister |url= http://www.adaderana.lk/news/54582/bombings-were-response-to-christchurch-shooting-state-minister |website= Ada derana |publisher=DeranaTV |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=AboutMotive2>{{cite news|url= https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/sri-lanka-attacks-churches-hotels-dle-intl/index.html|title=State Defense Minister: Bombings were retaliation for Christchurch killings|work=CNN|date=23 April 2019|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=AboutMotive3>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/asia/sri-lankan-attacks-retaliation-for-christchurch-minister-20190423-p51gkp.html|title=Sri Lankan attacks 'retaliation for Christchurch': minister|first=Matt|last=Wade|date=23 April 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref><ref name=AboutMotive4>{{cite news|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/sri-lanka-bombings-latest-updates/2019/04/22/f2afe32a-6531-11e9-a698-2a8f808c9cfb_story.html |title= Sri Lanka blasts were in retaliation for New Zealand mosque shootings, official says |work=Washington Post|date=23 April 2019 |accessdate= 23 April 2019}}</ref>|name=christchurch}} The direct linkage between the two attacks was questioned by [[New Zealand]]'s government and by some experts. The NTJ had been stockpiling explosives at least since January 2019.<ref name=\"ardern\" /><ref name=\"NZSrilanka\">{{cite news |title= Sri Lanka: Nearly 300 dead, Kiwi security expert says attacks unlikely to be linked to Christchurch |url= https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12224350 |work= NZ Herald |date= 23 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"dailymirror\">{{Cite web |url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/ISIS-fanatics-celebrate-SL-attacks/108-165731 |title=ISIS fanatics celebrate SL attacks |website= Daily mirror |access-date= 23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2019, [[Amaq News Agency]], a propaganda outlet for the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL), stated that \u2033the perpetrators of the attack targeting the citizens of coalition countries and Christians in Sri Lanka were Islamic State fighters\u2033.<ref name=\"isisindependent\">{{cite news |title= Sri Lanka bombings: Isis claims responsibility for deadly church and hotel attacks on Easter Sunday |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/sri-lanka-bombings-isis-terror-church-attack-easter-islamic-state-a8882231.html |work=The Independent |date=23 April 2019}}</ref> Sri Lanka was not part of the [[anti-ISIL coalition]], and the overwhelming majority of those killed were Sri Lankan citizens.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.news.com.au/world/asia/faces-of-terror-billionaire-loses-three-children-in-sri-lanka-attacks/news-story/e1ffa1d9d94e7e2eca0363471b55d46f|title= Easter bombings victims identified|date=22 April 2019|website=News |access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref> A man believed to be long-silent ISIL leader [[Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi]] praised the attackers during an 18-minute video on a range of topics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/abu-bakr-al-baghdadi-video-emerges-of-islamic-state-leader-alive-11707255|title=Abu Bakr al Baghdadi: Video emerges of 'Islamic State leader alive'|website=Sky News|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref> The [[Criminal Investigation Department (Sri Lanka)|Criminal Investigation Department]] has however stated that there was no evidence of its direct involvement and the group was convinced by the perpetrators to take responsibility.<ref name=\"Ravi\"/>\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Background ==\n{{Further|List of non-state terrorist incidents in Sri Lanka|Persecution of Christians in the modern era#Sri Lanka}}\nHistorically, [[terrorism in Sri Lanka]] mostly involved coordinated attacks by the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] (LTTE) against the [[Government of Sri Lanka|government]] and [[Sri Lanka Armed Forces|army]] during the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]], which began in 1983. The LTTE [[Eelam War IV|was defeated in 2009]] in its effort to violently seize control of [[Tamil Eelam|the northern and eastern coasts of the island]] from the [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]] ethnic majority to create an independent Tamil state. The [[Marxist-Leninist]] [[communist party|party]] [[Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna]] (JVP) also held uprisings in 1971 and 1987\u201389.<ref>[http://archives.dailynews.lk/2010/03/23/fea35.asp JVP and LTTE the twin menace that destroyed this Nation], A.A.M. Nizam, Daily News</ref><ref>[http://nparchive.news.lk/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=6100%3Atrying-to-shoo-the-eagle-away&Itemid=832 Trying to shoo the Eagle away] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826184513/http://nparchive.news.lk/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=6100:trying-to-shoo-the-eagle-away&Itemid=832 |date=26 August 2015}}, The Island</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=TOuSAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false The Separatist Conflict in Sri Lanka: Terrorism, Ethnicity, Political Economy], Asoka Bandarage</ref>\n\nThe main [[religion in Sri Lanka|religions in Sri Lanka]] are [[Buddhism]] (70.3%), [[Hinduism]] (12.6%), [[Islam]] (9.7%) and [[Christianity]] (6.1%),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/religious-beliefs-in-sri-lanka.html|title=Religious Beliefs in Sri Lanka|website=WorldAtlas|language=en|access-date=26 April 2019}}</ref> with 82% of the Christians being [[Catholic Church in Sri Lanka|Roman Catholics]]. The remaining Christians are evenly split between the [[Church of Ceylon|Anglican Church of Ceylon]] and other [[Protestantism|Protestant denominations]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mongabay.com/history/sri_lanka/sri_lanka-christianity.html | title = Sri Lanka&nbsp;\u2013 Christianity | publisher = [[Mongabay]]}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2010s, a low but persisting number of attacks and threats were made against Christian congregations and individuals, as well as other religious minorities, by local monks, although they may or may not be actual members of the Buddhist clergy.<ref>[https://www.srilankacampaign.org/ominous-rise-attacks-sri-lankas-christians/ Ominous rise in attacks on Sri Lanka's Christians]. Sri Lanka Campaign (17 May 2016). Retrieved 22 April 2019.</ref><ref>[http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Buddhists-destroy-a-church-in-Sri-Lanka.-Christians-continue-to-pray-under-a-tree-39658.html|Buddhists destroy a church in Sri Lanka. Christians continue to pray under a tree]. Asia News (14 January 2017). Retrieved 22 April 2019.</ref> Anglican [[Bishop of Colombo]] [[Dhiloraj Canagasabey]] called for constitutional rights on religion to be protected.<ref>[https://www.ucanews.com/news/sri-lanka-christians-protest-against-attacks/70164 Sri Lanka Christians protest against attacks]. UCA News (27 January 2017). Retrieved 22 April 2019.</ref> In 2018, the National Christian Evangelical Alliance of Sri Lanka (NCEASL) reported a large increase in the number of attacks against Christians in the country that year. This coincided with a Supreme Court ruling against a Catholic organisation in August, which deemed that [[proselytism]] was not protected by the constitution (though individual [[Freedom of religion in Sri Lanka|freedom of religion]] remained protected).<ref>[https://www.worldwatchmonitor.org/coe/sri-lanka-sharp-increase-in-violence-against-christians/ Sri Lanka: Sharp increase in violence against Christians]. World Watch Monitor (29 October 2018). Retrieved 22 April 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.refworld.org/pdfid/4be3e7042.pdf A Bill titled \"Provincial of the Teaching Sisters of the Holy Crossof the Third Order of Saint Francis in Menzingen of Sri Lanka (Incorporation)\"]. Supreme Court of Sri Lanka. Retrieved 22 April 2019.</ref>\n\n[[Easter Sunday]] is one of Christianity's holiest days and church attendance in Sri Lanka is very high on this day.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Khushbu|last1=Shah|first2=Sean|last2=Collins |title=Sri Lanka Easter Sunday attacks: what we know |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/4/21/18509739/sri-lanka-easter-sunday-attacks-what-we-know |website=Vox |accessdate=22 April 2019 |language=English |date=21 April 2019}}</ref> This was the first time since 2009, the end of the Sri Lankan Civil War, that the country had experienced a major terrorist attack.<ref name=\"SMH 210419\">{{cite web|url= https://www.smh.com.au/world/asia/scores-hurt-in-sri-lanka-easter-church-bombings-20190421-p51fyn.html |title=Hundreds killed, 450 injured as explosions rock Catholic churches during Easter mass |date= 22 April 2019|website= The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate= 22 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Islamic radicalisation ===\nThe Sri Lankan government was aware of some foreigners arriving in Sri Lanka to spread what justice minister [[Wijeyadasa Rajapakshe]] called [[Islamic extremism]]. In November 2016 he told parliament that 32 Sri Lankan Muslims from \"well-educated and elite\" families joined the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]].<ref name=\"Guardian 220419\">{{cite web |last1=Burke |first1=Jason |title=Sri Lanka bombings: doubts over Islamist group's potential role |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/22/sri-lanka-bombings-islamist-group-blamed-but-focus-also-on-failure-of-security-forces?CMP=Share_iOSApp_Other |website=The Guardian |accessdate=26 April 2019 |date=22 April 2019}}</ref> On 25 April 2019, Prime Minister [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]] revealed that the government had known of the Sri Lankan nationals who had joined Islamic State and returned to the country \u2013 but they couldn't be arrested, because joining a foreign terrorist organisation is not against the law.<ref name=\"Washington Post 250419\">{{cite web |last1=Tamkin |first1=Emily |title=How a legal blind spot could have kept Sri Lanka from arresting returning ISIS members |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/04/25/how-legal-blind-spot-could-have-kept-sri-lanka-arresting-returning-isis-members/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=26 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=No laws to arrest people who join foreign terrorist groups \u2013 PM Ranil Wickremesinghe \u2013 Sri Lanka Latest News |url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/04/26/no-laws-to-arrest-people-who-join-foreign-terrorist-groups-pm-ranil-wickremesinghe/ |website=Sri Lanka News \u2013 Newsfirst |accessdate=26 April 2019 |language=en |date=26 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"The Guardian 230419\">{{cite web |last1=Burke |first1=Jason |title=Scale of Sri Lankan attacks suggests Isis 'sub-contracted' bombings |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/23/isis-sub-contracted-sri-lanka-bombings-to-serve-its-own-ends |website=The Guardian |accessdate=26 April 2019 |date=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the bombings investigations revealed that school textbooks for Islam published by the government also encouraged radicalisation of Muslims. The school books since the 1980s called for the death sentence for those who leave Islam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.srilankaguardian.org/2019/06/sri-lankan-islamic-schools-textbooks.html|title=Sri Lankan Islamic schools textbooks recommended killings of non-Muslim|website=Sri Lanka Guardian|access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/article/1092785/education-ministry-to-probe-extremist-views-being-published-in-school-text-books|title=Sunday Times \u2013 Education Ministry to probe content being published in school text books|website=www.sundaytimes.lk|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Prior to the attacks ===\nVice president of the ''Muslim Council of Sri Lanka'' Hilmy Ahamed had said about three years ago he warned military intelligence officials about the [[National Thowheeth Jama'ath]], saying \"targeting the non-Muslim community is something they encourage \u2013 they say you have to kill them in the name of religion\".<ref name=\"Bloomberg 220419\">{{cite web |last1=Marlow |first1=Iain |title=Bloomberg \u2013 Are you a robot? |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-22/sri-lanka-muslims-had-warned-officials-about-group-behind-attack |website=www.bloomberg.com |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIndian intelligence agencies provided specific information to Sri Lankan authorities about the method and target locations for the potential terrorist attacks to Sri Lankan authorities as early as 4 April, and again on the night before, and as close as two hours, before the first attack. This included information about the threat to churches, gathered from interrogation of a suspected ISIL recruit in Indian custody.<ref name=\"ToI parliamentary probe\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/south-asia/sri-lanka-policeman-defies-president-to-testify-at-attack-probe/articleshow/69845448.cms|date=18 June 2019|website=Times of India|accessdate=18 June 2019|title=Sri Lanka policeman defies president to testify at attack probe}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN Indian Intelligence\">{{cite web|url= https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/23/asia/sri-lanka-investigation-ntj-intl/index.html|title=ISIS suspect gave advance warning of Sri Lanka bombings, source says |date= 23 April 2019|website= CNN |accessdate= 24 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters 230419\">{{cite web |last1=Aneez |first1=Shihar |last2=Sirilal |first2=Ranga |last3=Brock |first3=Joe |last4=Miglani |first4=Sanjeev |title=Exclusive: Sri Lanka was warned of threat hours before suicide... |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sri-lanka-blasts-warning-exclusive-idUSKCN1RZ1EC |website=Reuters |accessdate=26 April 2019 |language=en |date=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' and [[Agence France-Presse|AFP]] reported on a police chief warning security officials in an advisory ten days before the attacks of a threat to prominent churches from a [[Islamic fundamentalism|radical Islamist]] group, [[National Thowheeth Jama'ath]].<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/21/world/asia/sri-lanka-explosion.html|title=Police Warned That Sri Lanka Churches Were Bombing Targets|date=21 April 2019|website=[[The New York Times]]|url-access=limited|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref> No information in this regard had been passed to the senior politicians of the country;<ref name=\"deathtoll\" /><ref name=\"Blasts at Sri Lanka hotels and churches kill 156\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.afp.com/en/news/15/blasts-sri-lanka-hotels-and-churches-kill-156-doc-1ft48d4 |title=Blasts at Sri Lanka hotels and churches kill 156 |date=21 April 2019 |website=AFP |access-date=22 April 2019}}</ref> Minister [[Harin Fernando]] then tweeted images of an internal memo and report by the police intelligence of a terror attack planned by the founder of National Thowheeth Jama\u2019ath, Mohammed Zahran.<ref name=\"founder\" />\n\nInvestigators have said that Rilwan Hashim, brother of Zahran, had built the explosives alongside Mohammad Hasthoon. Zahran had claimed to have been appointed member of the Sri Lankan branch of Islamic State by one of its official and to be receiving orders directly from Syria, a claim investigators believe to have been fabricated. Zahran held a meeting in early April 2019 with over a dozen people in [[Panadura]], where they decided upon the attack. Some participants however wanted to target the Buddhist festivals<ref name=\"Pledge\"/>\n\nThe cohorts of Hashim had stayed in contact through [[Whatsapp]] and [[Telegram (software)|Telegram]]. The planning for a future attack may have begun in mid-2018, though the group hadn't selected any target. Investigators believe that the Easter attack plan came into being much later, with roles of perpetrators being decided upon only shortly before [[Easter]]. They had communicated through [[Threema]] a few weeks before the attack.<ref name=\"TheHindu25May\"/>\n\nIn January 2019 a stockpile of suspicious explosives were discovered near the Wilpattu National Park which contained 100 kilos of high explosives and 100 detonators. The Police confirmed that this was from a \"newly formed radical Muslim group\". On 16 April a parked motorcycle in Kattankudy carrying explosives detonated without casualties during a lightning storm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economynext.com/Sri_Lanka_seize_explosives_from_local_Islamist_radicals-3-13176-10.html|title=Sri Lanka seize explosives from local Islamist radicals|website=www.economynext.com|language=en|access-date=2 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=203298|title=Terrorist Motivations and Security Lapses Behind the Easter Carnage|website=www.island.lk|access-date=2 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/190428/news/lightning-thunder-and-a-blast-on-the-trail-of-terror-leader-347130.html|title=Lightning, thunder and a blast: On the trail of terror leader|website=The Sunday Times Sri Lanka|access-date=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Attacks ==\n[[File:Statue of Risen Jesus, Sri Lanka.jpg|thumb|Survived statue of Risen Jesus with blast marks and human blood after the Easter attack.]]\nChristians were attending Easter Sunday services when the bombings took place, targeting churches and hotels around Sri Lanka. The sequence and coordination of the bombings were planned to cause maximum destruction, targeting Christians during [[church service|worship services]] across the island nation, and targeting guests at the height of breakfast in luxurious beachfront hotels in the capital. All six of the first set of blasts targeting the churches and hotels were carried out by suicide bombers.<ref name=deathtoll>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/21/sri-lanka-attacks-death-toll-expected-rise-leaders-condemn-killings|title=Sri Lanka death toll expected to rise as leaders condemn killings |website=The Guardian|author=Burke, Jason|author2=Perera, Amantha|date=21 April 2019|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first blast took place in the [[St. Anthony's Shrine, Kochchikade|Shrine of St. Anthony]], a historic Catholic church in the capital, where more than 50 people were killed. The second blast took place in [[St. Sebastian's Church, Katuwapitiya|St. Sebastian's Church]] in the Christian-majority suburb of Negombo, to the north of Colombo and [[Sri Jayawardenepura Kotte]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.currentnewstimes.com/2019/04/SriLankaBombings.html|title=Who is behind the Sri Lanka bombings? \u2013 Current News Times|website=www.currentnewstimes.com|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref> Over 100 people were killed at St. Sebastian's Church.<ref>\"Sri Lanka Attacks: What We Know And Don't Know\"; New York Times:24 April. 2019</ref> St. Sebastian's is also close to Sri Lanka's main airport, [[Bandaranaike International Airport]], where security was heightened.<ref name=deathtoll />\n\nOn the other side of the island in Batticaloa, a bomb blast 15 minutes later killed 30 people at the Protestant evangelical [[Zion Church, Batticaloa|Zion Church]].<ref>\"Sri Lanka Attacks: What We Know And Don't Know\"; New York Times, 24 April 2019</ref>\n\nSri Lankan media reported at least 40 people killed in Colombo, between St. Anthony's and the hotels.<ref name=\"nytimes-21apr2019\"/><ref name=\"news1st-21apr2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/04/21/explosion-at-the-st-anthonys-church-in-kochikade/|title=LIVE: Death toll in Easter Sunday explosions crosses 160|last=Irugalbandara|first=Ramesh|date=21 April 2019|work=[[News First]]|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Timeline of the bombings<ref name=\"timeline\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/190428/columns/easter-sunday-massacres-where-do-we-go-from-here-347090.html|title=Easter Sunday massacres: Where do we go from here?}}</ref>\n!scope=\"col\"|Time ([[UTC+05:30]])\n!scope=\"col\"|Locations<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/22/sri-lanka-bombings-a-timeline-and-visual-guide|title=Sri Lanka bombings \u2013 a timeline and visual guide|last=Malone|first=Theresa|date=22 April 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=23 April 2019|last2=Levett|first2=Cath|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\"roar 210419\">{{cite web |last1=Thomas |first1=Kris |title=Easter Sunday Explosions in Sri Lanka: An Evolving Timeline of Events |url=https://roar.media/english/life/in-the-know/easter-sunday-explosions-in-sri-lanka/ |website=Roar Media |accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|8:25 AM\n|\n'''Colombo:''' [[St. Anthony's Shrine, Kochchikade|Shrine of St. Anthony Church]]\n|-\n|8:45 AM\n|'''Negombo:''' [[St. Sebastian's Church, Katuwapitiya|St.Sebastian's Church]]\n|-\n|9:05 AM\n|'''Batticaloa:''' [[Zion Church, Batticaloa|Zion Church]]\n|-\n|9.15 \u2013 9.20 AM\n|{{unbulleted list|'''Colombo:''' [[Cinnamon Grand Hotel]], [[The Kingsbury|Kingsbury Hotel]], [[Shangri-La Hotel, Colombo|Shangri-La Hotel]]}}\n|-\n|2:00 PM\n|'''Dehiwala''': [[Tropical Inn]]\n|-\n|2:15 PM\n|'''Dematagoda''': Housing complex\n|}\n\n=== Churches ===\nThe Catholic [[St. Anthony's Shrine, Kochchikade|Shrine of St. Anthony]] in [[Kotahena]], Colombo, was the first to be hit, followed by the Catholic Church of St. Sebastian in [[Negombo]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/04/21/sri-lanka-explosions-casualties-churches-hotels-targeted-easter/|title= Sri Lanka bombings: Intelligence blunder ahead of terror attack that killed more than 200|last= Smith |first=Nicola|date= 21 April 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date= 24 April 2019 |last2= Fernando|first2=Susitha |language= en-GB|issn=0307-1235|last3=Irshad|first3=Qadijah|last4= Swerling|first4= Gabriella}}</ref> Sri Lankan news media initially reported at least 93 people killed at St. Sebastian's.<ref name=\"nytimes-21apr2019\" /><ref name= news1st-21apr2019 /> In October 2019, the [[BBC]] reported that a total of 115 people had died in the St. Sebastian's bombing, including 27 children.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-asia-50097068/sri-lanka-bombings-forgiving-and-fighting-to-recover</ref>\n\nThe [[Zion Church, Batticaloa|Zion Church]] in [[Batticaloa]], a Protestant congregation, was also bombed.<ref name=\"NYTimes\" /> Local news reported at least 30 killed in Batticaloa,<ref name=\"nytimes-21apr2019\" /><ref name= news1st-21apr2019 /> with 9 of these reported by a police official to be tourists.<ref name= bbc-21apr2019 /> A hospital official in the region said that more than 300 people had been admitted following the explosion.<ref name=\"guardian-20apr2019\" /> The BBC reported that the suicide bomber had attempted to enter the church under the guise of filming it, but was denied access because of the ongoing service. Instead, he detonated his bomb in the churchyard, killing many children from the attached Sunday school who were taking a break.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-48034689|title=The worshipper who blocked a bomber|first=Rajini|last=Vaidyanathan|date=24 April 2019|accessdate=25 April 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Hotels ===\nThree 5-star hotels on the beachfront in central Colombo were attacked around the same time as the churches: the [[Shangri-La Hotel, Colombo|Shangri-La Hotel]], the [[Cinnamon Grand Hotel]] and [[The Kingsbury]].<ref name=\"nytimes-21apr2019\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2019/04/21/local/183395/three-more-explosions-kingsbury-shangri-la-cinnamon-grand|title=Three more explosions Kingsbury, Shangri-La, Cinnamon Grand|website=Daily News|access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Shangri-La bombers struck at 08:57 hours ([[UTC+05:30]]) during breakfast in the Table One Restaurant on the hotel's third floor, which was reportedly full of foreign tourists who made up the bulk of the hotel's clientele.<ref name=\"nytimes-21apr2019\" />\n\nThe suicide bomber who struck at the Taprobane restaurant in the Cinnamon Grand hotel had checked into the hotel with a false name the night before, claiming to be on a business trip. The bomber entered the queue of the packed restaurant's breakfast buffet the next morning and detonated explosives strapped to his back as he was about to be served. One of the hotel's managers who was welcoming guests was among those killed instantly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/sri-lanka-bomber-queued-hotel-buffet-then-unleashed-002105741.html|title=Sri Lanka bomber queued at hotel buffet then unleashed devastation|website=Yahoo News|access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe reception hall of a [[guest house]], the [[Tropical Inn]] in [[Dehiwala]], was also attacked later in the day, with two deaths reported.<ref name=\"TropicalIndy\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/sri-lanka-blast-news-latest-bombing-death-toll-attack-colombo-a8879796.html|title=Seventh bomb explosion heard at Sri Lanka Tropical Inn as Easter Sunday attacks continue|date=21 April 2019|website=The Independent|access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news/54499/another-explosion-near-dehiwala-zoo|title=Another explosion rocks Dehiwala|access-date=21 April 2019|website=Ada Derana|date=21 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/sri-lanka-bomb-blasts-live-updates-eighth-blast-occurs-in-colombos-orugodawatta-no-casualties-reported-yet-6487641.html|title=Sri Lanka bomb blasts LIVE updates: Eighth blast occurs in Colombo's Orugodawatta, no casualties reported yet|website=Firstpost|access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref> Later on during investigations, It was found that the bomber's original target had being the [[Taj Hotels|Taj Samudra]] Hotel in [[Colombo]]. CCTV footage given to the media by the hotel, shows the bomber attempting to detonate his vest three times in the dining area and upon failing, leaving the premises at 8.49 a.m.<ref>{{cite news |title='Nervous' bomber at lodge in Dehiwala captured on CCTV |url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news/54750/nervous-bomber-at-lodge-in-dehiwala-captured-on-cctv |accessdate=1 May 2019 |work=Ada Derana |date=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Kingsbury hotel management resumed their operations on 24 April 2019 followed by Cinnamon Grand few days later; Shangri-La partially reopened on 12 June 2019.{{efn|''See''<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2019/04/25/finance/183757/kingsbury-colombo-back-business|title=Kingsbury Colombo back to business|website=Daily News|access-date= 25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://economynext.com/Sri_Lanka_s_The_Kingsbury_hotel_to_reopen_Wednesday_following_Easter_bombings-3-14172.html|title=Sri Lanka's The Kingsbury hotel to reopen Wednesday following Easter bombings |website= Economy Next |access-date= 19 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.traveldailymedia.com/shangri-la-hotel-in-colombo-to-reopen-after-deadly-easter-attacks/|title=Shangri-La Hotel in Colombo to reopen after deadly Easter attacks |date= 22 April 2019 |website= Travel Daily |access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/sri-lanka-easter-bombings-official-statement-by-shangri-la-group/|title=Sri Lanka Easter bombings: Official statement by Shangri La Group \u2013 Lanka Business Online|last=LBO|language=en-US|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref>|name=closed}}\n\n=== Residence ===\nA further bombing occurred later in the day when police executed a breach and clear at a suspect's house in the suburbs of Colombo; in [[Dematagoda]] killing three police officers and four others at the premises including the suicide bomber.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/sri-lanka-easter-sunday-explosions-dle-intl/h_938e20e0c5f54865b718f5c1ffde81b7|title=BREAKING: Three police officers killed in house raid|date=21 April 2019|website= CNN |access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | website= BBC News |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-asia-48002165|title=Attacks on Sri Lanka churches and hotels|access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref> The pregnant suicide bomber, whose three children were killed in the blast, was the wife of Ilham Ibrahim, the Shangri-La suicide bomber, and the sister-in-law of Inshaf Ahmed Ibrahim, the Cinnamon Grand suicide bomber.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/asia/sri-lanka-bombings-the-wealthy-family-behind-the-suicide-attacks-20190425-p51h0n.html|title=Pregnant wife of Sri Lanka bomber detonated suicide vest|first=Bill Gardner and Ben|last=Farmer|date=25 April 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nThe government closed facilities for security; the [[Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka)|Defence Ministry]] issued a [[Curfew#Sri Lanka|police curfew]] starting at 18:00 local time on the day of the attacks, and imposed a temporary social media ban,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afp.com/en/news/717/blasts-sri-lanka-hotels-and-churches-kill-nearly-160-doc-1ft48d5|title=Blasts at Sri Lanka hotels and churches kill nearly 160|date=21 April 2019|publisher=Agence France-Presse|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> whilst the Minister of Education, [[Akila Viraj Kariyawasam]], had all schools closed for the following two days.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.dailynews.lk/2019/04/21/local/183398/all-schools-closed-tomorrow-day-after|title=All schools closed tomorrow & day after|website= Daily News |access-date= 21 April 2019}}</ref> The [[Colombo Stock Exchange]] announced that its operations will be temporarily suspended following the terror attacks, not opening as planned on 22 April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/00458caa-648e-11e9-9adc-98bf1d35a056|title=Colombo Stock Exchange trading suspended temporarily following the Easter massacre|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=22 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bizenglish.adaderana.lk/cse-will-not-open-for-trading-at-the-regular-time-on-monday/|title=CSE won't open at regular time on Monday|website=bizenglish.adaderana.lk|access-date=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn [[improvised explosive device]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oneindia.com/international/suicide-bombers-rdx-what-made-the-colombo-bombings-so-lethal-2881104.html|title=Suicide bombers, RDX: What made the Colombo bombings so lethal \u2013 Oneindia News|date=21 April 2019|website=www.oneindia.com|language=en|access-date=23 April 2019}}</ref> was found near the [[Bandaranaike International Airport]] in Colombo and was dismantled by the [[Sri Lankan Air Force]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-48008073 |title=Sri Lanka attacks: Death toll soars to 290 after bombings hit churches and hotels |website=BBC News |date=22 April 2019 |accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April, the [[Special Task Force]] (STF), the elite counter-terrorism unit of the [[Sri Lanka Police]], located a van belonging to the attackers near [[St. Anthony's Shrine, Kochchikade|St. Anthony's Shrine]], the site of one of the prior day's blasts. Upon inspection, the vehicle was found to have been rigged with 3 bombs. After the STF's bomb defusing unit evacuated the surrounding area, the bombs were detonated simultaneously during a defusing attempt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/5189848/sri-lanka-church-explosion-van-bomb/|title=Van explodes near Sri Lanka church while police try to defuse bomb|website=Global News|access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref> The same day, police reportedly found 87 items of bomb paraphernalia at the Bastian Mawatha Private Bus Station in Pettah.<ref name=guardian22aprillive />\n\nOn 25 April, the [[Criminal Investigation Department (Sri Lanka)|Criminal Investigation Department]] (CID) released names and photos of six suspects wanted in connection over the Easter Sunday bombings, seeking public assistance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernandopulle |first1=Sheain |title=Easter Sunday terror attack: Police seek public support to trace suspects |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Easter-Sunday-terror-attack:-Police-seek-public-support-to-trace-suspects/108-165945 |accessdate=25 April 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |date=25 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref> On 28 April, police confirmed two of the suspects, Mohomed Iwuhaim Saadiq Abdul Haq and Mohomed Iwuhaim Shahid Abdul Haq, who were arrested in [[Nawalapitiya]] and would be handed over to the CID.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two wanted suspects arrested in Nawalapitiya over Easter Sunday attacks |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Two-wanted-suspects-arrested-in-Nawalapitiya-over-Easter-Sunday-attacks/108-166081 |accessdate=28 April 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |date=28 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nSince the attacks, any garment covering the face including the burqa and niqab, have been banned in Sri Lanka.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-48088834|title=Sri Lanka bans face coverings after attacks|date=29 April 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Victims ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable floatright\" style=\"font-size:85%; text-align:left; margin:0 0 1.5em 1.5em;\"\n|+ Dead by citizenship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/south-asia/us-official-wounded-in-sri-lanka-easter-bombing-succumbs-to-her-injuries-in|title=US official wounded in Sri Lanka Easter bombing dies from her injuries in Singapore|website=The Straits Time}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;  | Citizenship\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Number\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{flag|Sri Lanka}}\n| 213\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{flag|India}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka blasts: 11 Indians dead, bodies of 7 JDS members to reach Karnataka|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/world/story/sri-lanka-blasts-11-indians-dead-bodies-of-7-jds-members-to-reach-karnataka-1508758-2019-04-24#close-overlay|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n|11\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{flag|United Kingdom}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka attacks: Eight Britons killed in explosions|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-48004465|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n|8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{flag|China}}<ref>{{cite news|title=\u75db\u5fc3\uff01\u65af\u91cc\u5170\u5361\u7206\u70b8\u5171\u81f46\u540d\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u9047\u96be|url=https://baijiahao.baidu.com/s?id=1632291588864126258|publisher=\u4eba\u6c11\u65e5\u62a5|accessdate=1 May 2019}}</ref>\n|6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{flag|Denmark}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Three children of Danish billionaire killed in Sri Lanka attacks|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sri-lanka-blasts-denmark/three-children-of-danish-billionaire-killed-in-sri-lanka-attacks-idUSKCN1RY0IB|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n|3\n|-\n|{{flag|Netherlands}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Nog twee Nederlandse slachtoffers onder doden Sri Lanka |url=https://www.volkskrant.nl/nieuws-achtergrond/nog-twee-nederlandse-slachtoffers-onder-doden-sri-lanka-onderzoek-stadsvijvers-even-schadelijk-voor-klimaat-als-duizenden-auto-s~b5c0c841/ |website=[[Volkskrant]] |publisher=Volkskrant |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n|3{{efn|One of whom a dual Swiss-Dutch citizen and another a dual Dutch-Sri Lankan citizen}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{flag|United States}}<ref name=\"ndtv.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/04/22/celebrity-chef-children-denmark-billionaire-among-dead-sri-lanka-bomb-attacks/|title=A billionaire's children, a D.C. fifth-grader, a celebrity chef: the victims in Sri Lanka|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n|3\n|-\n|{{flag|Australia}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Two Australians confirmed dead in Sri Lanka Easter Sunday terror attacks|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/22/two-australians-confirmed-dead-in-sri-lanka-easter-sunday-terror-attacks|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{flag|Saudi Arabia}}<ref name=aawsat>{{Cite news|url=https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/1691521/2-saudis-among-victims-sri-lanka-bombings|title=2 Saudis among Victims of Sri Lanka Bombings|date=23 April 2019 |work=Asharq Al-Awsat|access-date=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=Saudi-Airlines>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/svmedia_center/status/1120621486346207232|title=Saudi Arabian Airlines Statement|date=23 April 2019 |work=Twitter|access-date=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{flag|Spain}}<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite news|title=Una pareja de espa\u00f1oles, entre las v\u00edctimas mortales de los atentados de Sri Lanka|url=https://elpais.com/politica/2019/04/22/actualidad/1555949479_395920.html|accessdate=22 April 2019 |work=El Pa\u00eds|date=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{flag|Turkey}}<ref>{{cite news|title=2 Turkish engineers among dead in Sri Lanka bombings|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/2-turkish-engineers-among-dead-in-sri-lanka-bombings/1458989|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n|2\n|-\n|{{flag|Bangladesh}}<ref name=\"Bangladeshi_victim-1\">{{cite news|title=Sheikh Selim's minor grandson dies in Sri Lanka bombings |url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2019/04/21/sheikh-selims-minor-grandson-dies-in-sri-lanka-bombings |accessdate=22 April 2019 |work=bdnews24.com|date=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n|1\n|-\n|{{flag|Japan}}<ref>{{cite news|title=One Japanese national killed, four others injured as Sri Lanka attacks rock expat community|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2019/04/22/national/taro-kono-sends-sympathy-sri-lanka-terror-attacks-amid-report-japanese-among-fatalities/|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{flag|Portugal}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Rui Lucas morreu \u00e0s m\u00e3os dos terroristas no Sri Lanka. Portugu\u00eas de 31 anos estava em lua de mel|url=https://www.cmjornal.pt/portugal/detalhe/rui-lucas-morreu-as-maos-dos-terroristas-no-sri-lanka-portugues-de-31-anos-estava-em-lua-de-mel|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{flag|Switzerland}}<ref name=guardian22aprillive />\n|1\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Total\n| 259\n|}\n\nThe bombings killed 259 people and injured at least 500.<ref name=\"dailymirror20191003\" /><ref name=\"asiatimes20191209\" /> Initially, 359 fatalities were reported; the Ministry of Health later reduced the number by 106 after cross-referencing DNA samples to body parts. The majority of the dead are Sri Lankans, with at least 45 foreigners among those killed.<ref name=\"ndtv.com\"/>\n\nThe victims included:\n* [[Shantha Mayadunne]], a Sri Lankan TV chef. Her daughter was also among the victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2019/04/22/local/183471/shantha-mayadunne-daughter-among-shangri-la-victims|title=Shantha Mayadunne, daughter among Shangri-La victims|first=Kapila Somaratne Panadura Group|last=Corr|website=Daily News|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n* Three of the four children of the multi-billionaire [[Anders Holch Povlsen]], [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]] of Danish clothing retailer [[Bestseller (company)|Bestseller]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/people/who-is-anders-povlsen-everything-you-need-to-know-about-scotland-s-biggest-landowner-1-4912668|title=Who is Anders Povlsen? Everything you need to know about Scotland's biggest landowner|website=www.scotsman.com}}</ref><ref name=\"tgasos\">{{cite news |last1=Goodley |first1=Simon |title=Three children of Asos billionaire killed in Sri Lanka attacks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/22/asos-billionaire-loses-three-children-sri-lanka-anders-holch-povlsen |accessdate=22 April 2019 |work=The Guardian |agency=The Guardian |date=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n* A maternal grandson of Bangladeshi politician [[Sheikh Selim]].<ref name=\"Bangladeshi_victim-1\" />\n\nAt least 45 children, including nine who were foreigners, were killed.<ref name=\"guardian22aprillive\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2019/apr/22/sri-lanka-attacks-bombings-live-news|title=Sri Lanka attacks: tributes paid as two more victims named \u2013 live news|website=The Guardian|date=22 April 2019|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"bbcdead\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-48002169|title=Sri Lanka attacks: Who are the victims?|website=BBC|date=22 April 2019|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"australians\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/23/australian-man-recalls-horror-of-finding-wife-and-daughter-dead-in-sri-lanka-attack|title=Australian man recalls horror of finding wife and daughter dead in Sri Lanka attack|website=The Guardian|date=22 April 2019|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> On 23 April, the first mass [[Christian burial|funeral]] was held at [[St. Sebastian's Church, Katuwapitiya]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-48019189|title=Sri Lanka attacks: Mass funeral on day of mourning|date=23 April 2019|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Subsequent events ===\n{{Main|Sainthamaruthu shootout}}\nOn 26 April, the [[Sri Lanka Army]] and the STF carried out a search operation in [[Sainthamaruthu]] where three explosions and a shootout occurred when they attempted to raid a suspected hideout following a tip-off. Three suicide bombers blew themselves up, killing nine of their family members, including three women and six children, while three other terrorists were shot dead by the soldiers. One civilian was caught in the crossfire and died, according to police, while a wounded woman and child were taken to hospital.{{efn|''See''<ref>{{cite news |title=Shootout in Sainthamarudu when forces raid suicide vest factory |url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/04/26/shootout-in-sainthamarudu/amp/ |accessdate=26 April 2019 |work=News First |date=26 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Police Curfew to be in effect until further notice in Kalmunai \u2013 Chavalakade and Samanthurai |url=http://www.hirunews.lk/215245/police-curfew-to-be-in-effect-until-further-notice-in-kalmunai-chavalakade-and-samanthurai |accessdate=26 April 2019 |work=Hiru News |date=26 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sri Lanka bombings: 15 die in blast during raid on suspected hideout |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-48074702 |accessdate=27 April 2019 |work=BBC News |date=27 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Slater |first1=Joanna |title=15 killed in Sri Lanka police raid at suspected terrorist hideout |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/sri-lanka-authorities-say-15-die-in-police-raid-at-home-of-suspected-terrorists/2019/04/27/de46eb64-686e-11e9-a698-2a8f808c9cfb_story.html |accessdate=27 April 2019 |work=The Washington Post |date=27 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sri Lanka attacks: Relatives of key suspect Zahran Hashim killed |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-48085525 |accessdate=28 April 2019 |work=BBC News |date=28 April 2019}}</ref>|name=kalmunai}}\n\nAnother search operation in [[Sammanthurai]] based on information received by the [[State Intelligence Service (Sri Lanka)|State Intelligence Service]] led to a house where a stock of more than 150 [[gelignite]] sticks, IS uniforms and flags, 100,000 metal balls, a drone, a van and a laptop were discovered.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stock of metal balls, gelatnite sticks, IS uniforms seized |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Stock-of-metal-balls--gelatnite-sticks--IS-uniforms-seized/108-166018 |accessdate=26 April 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |date=26 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Weerasinghe |first1=Chamikara |title=Bomb gear, suicide kit, seven suspects arrested in Ampara |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2019/04/27/local/183987/bomb-gear-suicide-kit-seven-suspects-arrested-ampara |accessdate=27 April 2019 |work=Daily News |date=27 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Watson |first1=Ivan |last2=Wright |first2=Rebecca |last3=Champika |first3=Ajith |title=Sri Lanka imposes extended curfew after security forces found ISIS flags and explosives |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/26/asia/sri-lanka-bombings-suspect-intl/index.html |accessdate=26 April 2019 |work=CNN |date=26 April 2019}}</ref> An indefinite curfew was imposed in the police areas of Kalmunai, Chawalakade and Sammanthurai.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gun battle in Kalmunai: 15 including suicide bomber killed |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/top_story/Gun-battle-in-Kalmunai:-15-including-suicide-bomber-killed/155-166016 |accessdate=27 April 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |date=27 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the raids and arrests a second wave of planned attacks targeting several churches, opposing mosques and the [[Temple of the Tooth]] were averted<ref name=\"DM319\" />\n\nOn the same day, a suspect was arrested and more than 40 swords, kris knives and several uniforms similar to those worn by the army were recovered from a mosque at Palliyaweediya on [[Slave Island]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Weapons recovered from mosque at Slave Island |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Weapons-recovered-from-mosque-at-Slave-Island/108-166010 |accessdate=26 April 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |date=26 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 April, while conducting house to house raids in the [[Kalmunai]] area, evidence recovered linked three suspects to the murders of two police officers, Dinesh Alagaratnam and Niroshan Indika, on 29 November 2018 in [[Vavunathivu]]. All three suspects have been arrested and [[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)|The Daily Mirror]] reported that sources confirmed they were part of a \"radical Islamist\" group.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Farisz |first1=Hafeel |title=Vavunathiwu cop murders: Radical Islamists arrested, weapons recovered |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Vavunathiwu--cop-murders:-Radical-Islamists-arrested--weapons-recovered/108-166079 |accessdate=27 April 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |date=27 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day, the driver of the main suspect involved in the attacks, Mohamed Sahran, was arrested in [[Kattankudy]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Driver of main suspect in Sunday's bomb attacks arrested |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Driver-of-main-suspect-in-Sunday\u2019s-bomb-attacks-arrested/108-166078 |accessdate=27 April 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |date=27 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref> The Negombo Deputy Mayor, Mohomad Anzar, was taken into custody with a sword, a knife and 38 mobile phone batteries.<ref>{{cite news |title=Negombo Deputy Mayor arrested |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Negombo-Deputy-Mayor-arrested/108-166077 |accessdate=27 April 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |date=27 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\n[[File:President SIRISENA invokes emergency laws following Easter Sunday bombings.pdf|thumb|150px|link=https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/45/President_SIRISENA_invokes_emergency_laws_following_Easter_Sunday_bombings.pdf|Proclamation of emergency laws]]\n\n=== Precautionary measures ===\n==== State of emergency ====\nFollowing President Sirisena's return to the island from Singapore on 22 April 2019, where he was on a personal visit, the Sri Lankan government declared a [[state of emergency]] from midnight of 22 April by an extraordinary gazette notification issued by the President under the Public Security Ordinance. This would give the government, police and the armed forces sweeping powers to undertake counter terrorism activities. The government also announced that it would hold a [[national day of mourning]] the following day. On 24 April, the [[Sri Lankan Parliament]] passed emergency regulations without a vote after a day-long debate. Emergency regulations give the police and armed forces powers to search, arrest and detain persons up to 24 hours without a warrant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/article/1085509/parliament-passes-regulations-related-to-state-of-emergency|title=Sunday Times \u2013 Parliament passes regulations related to State of Emergency|website=www.sundaytimes.lk}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 August 2019, the government lifted the state of emergency, following the normalising of the security situation.<ref>{{cite news |title=State of emergency lifted as security established \u2013 Minister |url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_19B/Aug25_1566744947CH.php |accessdate=27 August 2019 |publisher=Colombo Page}}</ref>\n\n==== Curfews ====\n{{Quote box\n |quote = After incidents occurred yesterday in the North Western Province, starting from Chilaw and spreading to Kuliyapitiya, Hettipola and other areas, we had to impose curfew last evening. There were incidents of youth involved in damaging and destroying property. So, I as Army Commander request and at the same time warn anyone who has planned to destroy or dishonour the orders given by the government or the Armed Forces, that we will take stern action. I say again we will take stern action to apprehend, arrest and even open fire and use minimum or maximum powers given under emergency laws.\n\nWe will ensure that the country will not return to violence, including the violence of radicalization and terrorists. Please ensure that you do not get involved in such illegal incidents or any such activities. The Armed Forces will not hesitate to use our powers to curb, curtail and contain the situation. The Armed Forces are strong enough to ensure there won\u2019t be an escalation of violence in any part of the island. We have deployed the Army, Navy and Air Force to assist the Police to maintain law and order. I humbly request the youth not to get involved in violence and get entangled with the Armed Forces where we are ready to use our powers.\n |author = [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Army Commander]] [[Mahesh Senanayake]]\n |source = [http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Will-not-hesitate-to-use-maximum-force:-Army-Commander/108-167086 Daily Mirror]\n |quoted = 1\n |qalign = left\n |width  = 30%\n}}\nSince 21 April evening, the government has imposed nightly [[Curfew#Sri Lanka|police curfews]] effective island-wide, with the hours reduced to 2200 to 0400 hours until 27 April. Indefinite curfews were imposed in several police divisions where incidents such as the [[Sainthamaruthu shootout]] took place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/international/sri-lanka-curfew-shut-down-access-to-social-media-729886.html|title=Sri Lanka: Curfew, shut down access to social media|date=21 April 2019|website=Deccan Herald}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 May, a group of people congregated in the town of [[Chilaw]] allegedly following a Facebook post which claimed there was a plan to attack the town. An immediate police curfew was imposed and the situation was brought under control without further damage. Two people were later arrested over the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Police-curfew-imposed-in-Chilaw/108-166957|title=Police curfew imposed in Chilaw|website=www.dailymirror.lk|accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 May, sporadic isolated incidents where groups of people vandalised property in the [[North Western Province, Sri Lanka|North Western Province]] caused police to impose curfew across the entire country. Acting Police Chief C.D. Wickramaratne promised an overwhelming police response against any individuals breaking the law by instigating sporadic countrywide riots targeting Muslim-owned property and businesses. In a hard-hitting statement, Army Commander [[Mahesh Senanayake]] stated that the security forces had been given broad-ranging powers under emergency laws, and would respond proportionately to the threat, but that they would not hesitate to utilise the full extent of their powers to ensure that the rule of law is maintained.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Stern-action-against-lawbreakers--warns-Acting-IGP/108-167084|title=Stern action against lawbreakers, warns Acting IGP|website=www.dailymirror.lk|accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 May, Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe stated that all necessary powers to restore peace and stability to the country had been given to security forces and police. He further stated that creating unnecessary disturbances would hinder the ongoing investigations to apprehend terrorists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Security-forces---police-given-all-powers-to-bring-back-normalcy-PM/108-167078|title=Security forces & police given all powers to bring back normalcy-PM|website=www.dailymirror.lk|accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = We will not let any elements or any cowardly acts of a few extremists drag the country to anarchy over the unfortunate events on Easter Sunday. We are receiving information on those responsible for such activities, and will take full action against them.\n |author = Acting IGP [[C. D. Wickramaratne|Wickramaratne]]\n |source = [http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Stern-action-against-lawbreakers--warns-Acting-IGP/108-167084 Daily Mirror]\n |quoted = 1\n |qalign = left\n |width  = 30%\n}}\n\n==== Ban on social media ====\nThe government temporarily blocked major [[social media]] networks and messaging services [[Facebook]], [[Instagram]], [[WhatsApp]], [[Viber]], [[Snapchat]] and [[YouTube]] within hours of the attack. The blocking included [[Virtual private network|VPN]] service providers that could be used to circumvent the blocks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Social Media Has Been Blocked For Over 24 Hours in Sri Lanka After The Deadly Explosions |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/sri-lanka-social-media-block |publisher=buzzfeednews |accessdate=23 April 2019 |date=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome commentators condoned the move and viewed it as evidence that social media sites had failed to stop misinformation.<ref name=\"cjrsrilanka\">{{cite web |last=Allsop |first=Jon |url=https://www.cjr.org/the_media_today/sri_lanka_attacks_facebook.php |title=After Sri Lanka bombings, a social media shutdown |work=Columbia Journalism Review |date=22 April 2019 |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> Others criticised the block for cutting off Sri Lankans from means of communicating with relatives during a disaster<ref>{{cite web |title=Sri Lanka attacks: Social media ban leaves Wellington families desperate for answers|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/world/112193040/sri-lanka-attacks-social-media-ban-leaves-wellington-families-desperate-for-answers|publisher=Stuff|accessdate=23 April 2019 |date=23 April 2019}}</ref> and saw it as counterproductive in reducing fake news.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sri Lanka's social media ban won't solve its misinformation problem|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/23/tech/facebook-ban-sri-lanka-intl/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=23 April 2019 |date=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sri Lanka's Decision to Block Social Media Highlights Rising Concerns from Governments |url=https://www.socialmediatoday.com/news/sri-lankas-decision-to-block-social-media-highlights-rising-concerns-from/553212/|publisher=Social Media Today|accessdate=23 April 2019 |date=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April, President Sirisena ordered the Telecommunications Regulatory Commission (TRC) to lift the social media ban.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanjeewa |first1=Darshana |title=President instructs TRC to lift ban on social media |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/President-instructs-TRC-to-lift-ban-on-social-media/108-166190 |accessdate=30 April 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |date=30 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tomlinson |first1=Hugh |title=Sri Lanka lifts social media ban despite risk of further attacks |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sri-lankan-social-media-ban-lifted-despite-further-attack-warnings-75l7jpk26 |accessdate=30 April 2019 |work=The Times |date=30 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gold |first1=Hadas |title=Sri Lanka lifts social media ban imposed after Easter bombings |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/30/tech/sri-lanka-social-media-ban/ |accessdate=30 April 2019 |work=CNN |date=30 April 2019}}</ref> On 13 May the government blocked social media for the third time following the anti-Muslim riots.<ref>{{cite news |title=Social media blocked for Sri Lankan users |url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/article/1087716/social-media-blocked-for-sri-lankan-users |accessdate=13 May 2019 |work=Sunday Times Online}}</ref>\n\n==== Ban on burqa ====\n{{See also|Hijab by country}}\nOn 24 April 2019, a Sri Lankan MP{{who|date=May 2019}} called for both [[burqa]] and [[Niq\u0101b|niqab]] to be banned from the country and proposed that a bill be passed in the Parliament during a local parliamentary session in wake of the attacks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Range |first1=Irangika |title=Ban 'niqab, burqa' \u2013 Prof. Ashu |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2019/04/24/local/183684/ban-\u2018niqab-burqa\u2019-prof-ashu |accessdate=30 April 2019 |work=Daily News |date=24 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Withnall |first1=Adam |title=Sri Lankan MP calls for burqa ban in wake of Easter massacre |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/sri-lanka-bombing-burqa-ban-isis-islam-ashu-marasinghe-a8883801.html |accessdate=30 April 2019 |work=The Independent |date=24 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Irshad |first1=Qadijah |title=Sri Lanka attacks: Fear of retaliation against Muslims grows as MP calls for burqa ban |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/sri-lanka-attacks-burqa-ban-muslims-terrorism-bombings-a8885056.html |accessdate=30 April 2019 |work=The Independent |date=24 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April 2019, President Sirisena banned any type of face covering that prevents or hinders facial identification, including the [[burqa]] or [[niq\u0101b]] under an emergency law which will go into force on 29 April 2019. This law does not prevent a Muslim woman from wearing a [[hijab]] or [[chador]]. Breaching any emergency law is punishable by a maximum penalty of death, a recently reinstated penalty which has not been used for more than four decades.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Steinbuch |first1=Yaron |title=Sri Lanka looking for executioners as death penalty reinstated |url=https://nypost.com/2019/02/13/sri-lanka-looking-for-executioners-as-death-penalty-reinstated/ |accessdate=28 April 2019 |work=New York Post |date=13 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In a press release, the President stated the decision was taken to \"further support the ongoing security and help the armed forces to easily identify the identity of any wanted perpetrators\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Waldrop |first1=Theresa |title=Sri Lanka bans burqas for 'public protection' after bomb attacks |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/28/asia/sri-lanka-bans-burqa/index.html |accessdate=28 April 2019 |work=CNN |date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The All Ceylon Jamiyyathul Ulema also told all Muslim women not to wear face veils in public for security reasons.\n\n==== Surveillance ====\nOn 10 May 2019, it was mandated that copies of all sermons given inside mosques be submitted to the Ministry of Muslim Religious and Cultural Affairs, as part of a broader strategic plan to monitor activities inside mosques. The Ministry said mosques must not be used for radicalising congregations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sri Lanka imposes controls on mosques after suicide bombings |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/south-asia/sri-lanka-slaps-controls-on-mosques-after-islamist-attacks |accessdate=11 May 2019 |work=The Straits Times |date=10 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Centralised and Integrated Population Information System ====\nOn 8 May 2019, Prime Minister Wickremesinghe announced plans for a centralised platform for the collection, monitoring and storage of intelligence. The system known as the Centralised and Integrated Population Information System will collect biometric data from iris scanning and facial identification at all ports of entry and exit. The Ministry of Internal Affairs, Provincial Councils and local governments were instructed to prepare an action plan for this system in two weeks, to obtain Cabinet approval.<ref>{{cite news |title=Data protection |url=http://www.ft.lk/ft-view/Data-protection/58-677950 |accessdate=11 May 2019 |work=Daily FT |date=10 May 2019 |language=English}}</ref>\n\n=== Investigations ===\n==== Security lapse Inquiry ====\nSri Lanka's Minister of Telecommunication [[Harin Fernando]] had tweeted that Inspector General of Police [[Pujith Jayasundara]] sent an alert by his Deputy Inspector General Priyalal Dissanayake dated 11 April 2019 relaying an Indian intelligence report<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/south-asia/pakistani-jihadis-rising-in-sri-lanka-india-warned/articleshow/68998049.cms|title=sri lanka news: Lashkar has fanned radicalism in Sri Lanka \u2013 Times of India|last=23 Apr|first=Bharti Jain {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2019|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=23 April 2019|last3=Ist|first3=13:34}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/sri-lanka-easter-blasts-nia-had-intelligence-on-blasts/article26914273.ece|title=Sri Lanka Easter blasts: NIA had intelligence on blasts|last=Kumar|first=S. Vijay|date=22 April 2019|work=The Hindu|access-date=23 April 2019|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/india-warned-sri-lanka-about-suicide-bombings-why-didnt-island-nation-act-796390|title=India warned Sri Lanka about suicide bombings, but why didn't the island nation act?|last=Malik|first=Bismah|date=22 April 2019|website=International Business Times, India Edition|language=english|access-date=22 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/despite-indias-warning-sri-lanka-failed-to-take-precautions-pm-ranil-wickremesinghe-admits-colombo-had-intel-on-blasts-2111317.html|title=Despite India's Warning, Sri Lanka 'Failed' to Take Precautions; PM Admits Colombo Had Intel on Blasts|website=News18|access-date=22 April 2019}}</ref> from 4 April that suicide bombers affiliated with NTJ planned to attack prominent churches and the [[India House (Colombo)|Indian embassy in Colombo]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Harin tweets intelligence memo warning of a planned attack |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Harin-tweets-intelligence-memo-warning-of-a-planned-attack/108-165676 |accessdate=22 April 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |location=Sri Lanka |date=21 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sri Lanka : Minister releases intelligence letter warning of church attacks, questions why action was not taken |url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_19A/Apr21_1555866043CH.php |accessdate=22 April 2019 |work=colombopage.com |agency=ColomboPage News Desk |date=21 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lanka Top Cop Had Warned of Suicide Attack on Indian Embassy Too: Report |url=https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/sri-lanka-blasts-sri-lanka-top-cop-had-warned-of-bombers-targeting-churches-10-days-ago-2026290 |accessdate=22 April 2019 |work=NDTV.com |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=22 April 2019}}</ref> The Indian intelligence service reissued the warnings two days and two hours before the attacks. Following the attacks, it disclosed that some of the information about the attacks was gleaned from an ISIL suspect arrested in [[Delhi]], who revealed the name of a man, Zahran Hashim, the founder of the NTJ.<ref name=\"founder\" /><ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/23/asia/sri-lanka-investigation-ntj-intl/index.html|title=ISIS suspect gave advance warning of Sri Lanka bombings, source says|author=James Griffiths and Swati Gupta|website=CNN|access-date=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter initial government denials of the alert's authenticity, Prime Minister [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]] stated that \"information was there,\" about the attacks, and that his government must \"look into why adequate precautions were not taken.\"<ref name=\"deathtoll\" /> The State Defence Minister had earlier requested that the media not publish the names of the attackers, and said the government believes the attacks were carried out by a single group of religious extremists.<ref name=\"NYTimes\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Sri Lanka's gov't 'alerted to possible attacks before bombings' |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/04/sri-lanka-gov-alerted-attacks-bombings-190421165822214.html |accessdate=22 April 2019 |work=Al Jazeera |date=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n;TID pre-bombing investigation \nIt was later claimed that the Police Terrorism Investigations Division (TID) has been investigating the activities of the chief suspect Zahran, with an [[arrest warrant]] issued by the Colombo Magistrate's Court in August 2018 based on a 'B' report dated 2 July 2018 which the TID had submitted. However, the investigation had stopped after the arrest of the head of the TID, DIG [[Nalaka de Silva]] in September 2018, on allegations of attempting to assassinate President Sirisena, which ignited the [[2018 Sri Lankan constitutional crisis|2018 constitutional crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/190526/news/zaharan-had-an-open-warrant-for-his-arrest-since-last-year-351015.html|title=Zaharan had an open warrant for his arrest since last year}}</ref>\n\n;Presidential Commission of Inquiry\nThis security lapse forms part of a current [[Presidential Commission of Inquiry on the Easter Attacks|Presidential Commission of Inquiry into the Easter Sunday bombings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/04/sri-lanka-bombings-latest-updates-190421092621543.html|title=Sri Lanka bombings: All the latest updates|website=www.aljazeera.com|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref> The commission submitted an interim report two weeks after the attack and extension of its term until 31 May to complete the final report.\n\nBased on the interim report of the presidential commission, the [[Attorney General of Sri Lanka|Attorney General]] Dappula de Livera instructed the [[Criminal Investigation Department]] to carryout a criminal investigation against former Defence Secretary Hemasiri Fernando and IGP Pujith Jayasundera to determine if they failed to act on intelligence warnings about the attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/190519/news/former-defence-secretary-and-igp-face-criminal-charges-349993.html|title=Former Defence Secretary and IGP face criminal charges}}</ref> The final report was presented to President Sirisena by the commission on 10 June 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Easter-Sunday-attack:-Committee-submits-final-report-to-prez/108-169020|title=Easter Sunday attack: Committee submits final report to prez|website=www.dailymirror.lk}}</ref>\n\n;Parliamentary Select Committee\nIn May, a Parliamentary [[Select Committee]] (PSC) was appointed to probe the Easter Sunday terrorist attacks and incidents in its aftermath by the [[Speaker of the Parliament of Sri Lanka|Speaker of the Parliament]]. The Select committee is headed by the Deputy Speaker Ananda Kumarasiri and includes seven MPs. The [[SLFP]] and the [[UPFA]] decided not to participate in the Select committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2019/05/16/local/185787/psc-probe-easter-sunday-carnage-other-mob-attacks|title=PSC to probe Easter Sunday carnage, other mob attacks|first=Asela|last=KURULUWANSA|website=Daily News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Eight-member-PSC-headed-by-Deputy-Speaker-appointed/108-167749|title=Eight member PSC headed by Deputy Speaker appointed|website=www.dailymirror.lk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Easter-Sunday-attacks:-SLFP--UPFA-decide-not-to-take-part-in-PSC/108-167739|title=Easter Sunday attacks: SLFP, UPFA decide not to take part in PSC|website=www.dailymirror.lk}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 June 2019, President Sirisena called an emergency Cabinet meeting and protest the PSC probe. He ordered that the PSC be terminated. He was critical of the PSC for summering intelligence and police officers. He had ordered no public officer to appear for summons issued by the PSC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/President-disputes-PSC-probe/108-168931|title=President disputes PSC probe|website=www.dailymirror.lk}}</ref> Following Chief of National Intelligence [[Sisira Mendis]]'s statement at the PSC to the effect that President Sirisena knew about the warnings of an impending attack, Sirisena sacked Mendis within hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/world/2019/06/sri-lanka-bombings-intelligence-chief-sacked.html|title=Sri Lanka bombings: Intelligence chief sacked}}</ref>\n\n==== Bombing investigation ====\nThe [[Sri Lankan Police]] launched an investigation into the incident; it has now transpired into a major transnational investigation led by the [[Criminal Investigation Department (Sri Lanka)|Criminal Investigation Department]] of the Sri Lankan Police to hunt down all the perpetrators involved in this incident. Six foreign police agencies, including [[Scotland Yard]], [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI), and [[Interpol]] are assisting the [[Sri Lankan Police]].<ref name=\"CNN 260419\" />\n\nThe bomber at the Cinnamon Grand Hotel was a guest who registered under the name of \"Mohamed Azzam Mohamed\" and gave a false address.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/sri-lanka-blast-suicide-bomber-waited-in-queue-for-easter-sunday-buffet-at-cinnamon-grand-hotel-1.1555849958833|title=Sri Lanka blast: Suicide bomber waited in queue for Easter Sunday buffet at Cinnamon Grand Hotel|website= Gulf news |access-date= 21 April 2019}}</ref> The Shangri-La Hotel bomber was identified by police as Insan Seelavan, a factory owner, nine of whose employees have been arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Shangri-La-suicide-bomber-identified/108-165730|title=Shangri-La suicide bomber identified|website=www.dailymirror.lk|language=English|access-date=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2019, three Sri Lankan government and military sources told Reuters that a Syrian national had been held in custody for questioning over the attacks.<ref name=SyrianInCustody>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sri-lanka-blasts-syrian-idUSKCN1RZ0CH|title=Sri Lanka detains Syrian for questioning over attacks|date=23 April 2019|access-date=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nLater on 23 April, the Sri Lankan State Defence Minister, [[Ruwan Wijewardene]], said that initial investigations have revealed that Islamic extremists \"carried out the attacks in retaliation for [[Christchurch mosque shootings|a March attack on two mosques in New Zealand]]\".<ref name=AboutMotive /><ref name=AboutMotive2 /><ref name=AboutMotive3 /><ref name=AboutMotive4 /> This has been questioned by New Zealand's Prime Minister [[Jacinda Ardern]] and by analysts, as the attacks were likely planned before the Christchurch attacks.<ref name=\"ardern\">{{cite news |title=New Zealand PM says no intelligence linking Sri Lanka attacks to Christchurch |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sri-lanka-blasts-newzealand/new-zealand-pm-says-no-intelligence-linking-sri-lanka-attacks-to-christchurch-idUSKCN1RZ2K4 |agency=Reuters |date=24 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NZSrilanka\" /><ref name=\"dailymirror\" /> New Zealand security expert Paul Buchanan said that \"Christchurch seems to be a convenient justification for something that was being planned before 15 March\".<ref name=\"NZSrilanka\" /> Shortly afterward, [[Amaq News Agency]] claimed [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) inspired the attacks.<ref name=\"isisindependent\" /> It released a photo and a video showing eight suicide bombers pledging allegiance to ISIL leader [[Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi]]. Zahran Hashim of the NTJ was identified as their leader.<ref name=\"auto5\" /> Amaq's statements emphasised the attacks were against Christians who are war with the organisation. None of them referenced Christchurch.<ref name=\"autolongwar\" />\n\nInvestigators believe the bombs were made of [[acetone peroxide]], and are looking into training camps that had been hidden on a remote compound near [[Wanathavilluwa]], on the west coast of the country, and possible links to overseas jihadist networks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/04/article/mother-of-satan-explosive-used-in-sri-lanka-bombings/|title=Asia Times {{!}} 'Mother of Satan' explosive used in Sri Lanka bombings {{!}} Article|last=Times|first=Asia|website=Asia Times|language=en|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Telegraph 240419\" />\n\nAccording to the investigators, the perpetrators were offered military training by a person named Army Mohideen, while weapons training was provided overseas as well as in Nuwara Eliya and Wanathawilluwa in the Eastern Province. The vehicles used in the attack are believed to have been procured from a car sales centre in Kadawata.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vital info on terror attacks revealed by arrested suspects |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Vital-info-on-terror-attacks-revealed-by-arrested-suspects/108-165963 |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Investigation Agency]] of India confirmed that on 28 April, four homes were raided in [[Kasaragod]] and [[Palakkad]], [[Kerala]] as part of the transnational investigation unfolding into the Easter Sunday bombings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/terror-mastermind-had-links-in-state/article26973608.ece|title=Sri Lanka terror mastermind had links in Kerala|first=G.|last=Anand|date=28 April 2019|accessdate=29 April 2019|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n\n== Perpetrators ==\n=== Arrests ===\nPolice arrested eight people living in the Colombo suburb of [[Dematagoda]] on the day of the attacks.{{efn|''See''<ref name=\"multiple blasts\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes\" /><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.cnn.com/asia/live-news/sri-lanka-easter-sunday-explosions-dle-intl/ |title=Sri Lanka explosions kill more than 200&nbsp;\u2013 live updates|date=21 April 2019|website= CNN |access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/21/sri-lanka-explosions-what-we-know-so-far|title=Sri Lanka explosions: what we know so far|last=Siddique|first=Haroon|date= 21 April 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 April 2019|language=en-GB|issn= 0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/21/asia/sri-lanka-explosions/ |title=Sri Lanka blasts: More than 200 dead in church and hotel bombings across country |first1 =Sugam | last1 = Pokharel | first2 = Euan | last2 = McKirdy | first3 = Tara | last3 =John|website=CNN|access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Easter Sunday bomb attacks kill more than 200 at Sri Lankan churches, hotels|agency=Thomson Reuters|date=21 April 2019|access-date=22 April 2019|publisher=CBC|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/sri-lanka-church-hotel-explosions-1.5105883}}</ref>|name=arrested}} Five more suspected attackers and accomplices were arrested at a house during the night. Police confirmed on the day after the bombings that 24 people were arrested.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sri Lanka bombings death toll rises to 290, 24 arrested in connection with multiple blasts |url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/world/sri-lanka-bombings-death-toll-rises-to-290-24-arrested-in-connection-with-multiple-blasts/1509475 |accessdate=22 April 2019 |work=Free Press Journal |agency=IANS |date=22 April 2019}}</ref> By 23 April, the number of people arrested was 40.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/world-news/sri-lankan-police-arrest-40-suspects-after-bombings-as-death-toll-rises-38041410.html|title=Sri Lankan police arrest 40 suspects after bombings as death toll rises|website=Independent.ie|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> Three police officers and two civilians were killed by bombs that exploded during the capturing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Giordano |first1=Chiara |title=Eighth explosion kills police officers in Sri Lanka as death toll from Easter Sunday bomb attacks rises to more than 200 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/sri-lanka-blast-news-latest-bombing-death-toll-attack-colombo-a8879796.html |accessdate=22 April 2019 |work=The Independent |date=21 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> By 24 April 60 people had been arrested with possible links to the attacks, with 32 in custody. On 26 April, the Sri Lankan Police had more than 70 suspects held on charges of suspicion of terrorism, aiding and abetting terrorism, and conspiracy to commit terrorism. Four high-level suspects are being held by the Terrorism Investigation Department, and 33 are being held by the [[Criminal Investigation Department (Sri Lanka)|Criminal Investigation Department]]. Most of them are friends and family of the suspected suicide bombers.<ref name=\"CNN 260419\" /><ref name=\"Telegraph 240419\">{{cite web |last1=Farmer |first1=Ben |last2=Smith |first2=Nicola |title=Sri Lanka suicide bomber 'studied in the UK', defence minister announces as death toll rises to 359 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/04/24/sri-lanka-suicide-bomber-studied-uk/ |website=The Telegraph |accessdate=26 April 2019 |date=24 April 2019}}</ref> Nine suicide bombers were involved in the attacks, and police have identified all of them.<ref name=\"The New York Times 240419\"/><ref name=\"bombers\"/>\n\nA suspected mastermind named Hayathu Mohamed Ahmed Milhan and four others were deported to Sri Lanka from the Middle East. Milhan was expected to become the new leader of NTJ.<ref name=\"DW 140619\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/sri-lanka-bombings-suspected-ringleader-arrested-in-middle-east/a-49210405|title=Sri Lanka bombings: Suspected ringleader arrested in Middle East|website=Deutsche Welle|date=14 June 2019|accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March 2020, the main suspect who was also the mastermind behind the Easter bombing in the Zion Church was arrested by police in Mount Lavinia during the curfew which was imposed indefinitely due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sri Lanka|coronavirus pandemic in the country]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2020/03/30/law-order/215376/zion-church-bombing-mastermind-arrested|title=Zion Church bombing mastermind arrested|last=Nathaniel|first=Camelia|website=Daily News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adaderana.lk/news/61996/main-suspect-of-suicide-bomb-attack-on-zion-church-arrested|website=adaderana.lk|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economynext.com/new-probe-into-cid-investigation-of-easter-attacks-ordered-62985,%20https://economynext.com/new-probe-into-cid-investigation-of-easter-attacks-ordered-62985/|title=New probe into CID investigation of Easter attacks ordered|date=2020-03-29|website=EconomyNext|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The suspect was identified as a 40 year old resident of Dehiwala/Mount Lavinia and was accused of transporting the suicide bomber to the Zion Church in Batticaloa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_20A/Mar29_1585491564CH.php|title=Sri Lanka : Main suspect of the Easter Sunday Bomb Attack on Zion Church Arrested|website=www.colombopage.com|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hirunews.lk/237501/the-main-suspect-who-directed-and-transported-the-suspect-of-the-zion-church-suicide-bombing-arrested|title=The main suspect who directed and transported the suspect of the Zion Church suicide bombing arrested|website=Hiru News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The suspect is also alleged of handling the suicide bomber who attack the Kochikade St. Anthony Church.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/print/front_page/Main-suspect-arrested-over-Zion-Church-bomb-attack/238-185835|title=Main suspect arrested over Zion Church bomb attack|website=www.dailymirror.lk|language=English|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==== Bail controversy ====\nNine people arrested on 22 April 2019 and formally charged with supplying equipment used in connection with an act of terrorism appeared in [[Magistrate's Courts of Sri Lanka|Colombo Magistrates Court]] on 6 May 2019. They were released on bail of two sureties of LKR500,000 each (approx. $3,000), as the court found the case against them was weak.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanjeewa Balasuriya |first1=Darshana |title=SIU probes to ascertain Wellampitiya police erred |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/top_story/SIU-probes-to-ascertain-Wellampitiya-police-erred/155-166699 |accessdate=9 May 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |date=9 May 2019 |language=English}}</ref> The police launched an investigation to determine whether Wellampitiya police had erred. On 9 May 2019, investigators found Wellampitiya police officers had made several errors, neglecting to put several facts before the court. A police spokesman said stern action would be taken against the officers responsible.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanjeewa Balasuriya |first1=Darshana |title=SIU probe finds Police had erred |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/SIU-probe-finds-Police-had-erred/108-166813 |accessdate=9 May 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |date=9 May 2019 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 May, Wellampitiya Police officers hit back against the allegations of negligence and filed a complaint to the Judicial Service Commission (JSC) alleging Colombo Magistrate Court Judge Priyantha Liyanage was being biased against the police by releasing nine of the ten suspects produced in court. A legal representative appearing on behalf of the suspects stated that the magistrate nor his client needs to wait for the police to complete its investigations for the magistrate to make a decision on the matter, the allegations made by the Wellampitiya Police officers do not have a proper basis in law. A police spokesman said an investigation had been launched into the incident, and that it appears that police may have erred by not filing the case under the [[Prevention of Terrorism Act (Sri Lanka)|Prevention of Terrorism Act]] because the investigations were yet to be completed. He further stated that as soon as the report from the investigation is released, police will take actions against any personnel held responsible.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Wellampitiya-Police-OIC-demands-inquiry/108-167146|title=Wellampitiya Police OIC demands inquiry|website=www.dailymirror.lk}}</ref>\n\n=== National Thowheeth Jama'ath ===\n{{Main|National Thowheeth Jama'ath}}\nHealth Minister [[Rajitha Senaratne]] confirmed that all of the bombers were Sri Lankan citizens associated with [[National Thowheeth Jama'ath]] (NTJ), a local militant radical Islamist group, but foreign links are suspected.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Latest: Sri Lanka: local militants carried out attacks |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/news/crime/article/The-Latest-Curfew-lifted-after-Sri-Lankan-13784450.php |accessdate=22 April 2019 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |agency=Associated Press |date=22 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422091123/https://www.sfchronicle.com/news/crime/article/The-Latest-Curfew-lifted-after-Sri-Lankan-13784450.php |archive-date=22 April 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref> There had been no claim of responsibility before 23 April. NTJ's leadership had been condemned by several Sri Lankan Muslim organisations in 2016 for advocating extreme fundamentalist indoctrination of children and for clashes with Buddhist monks,<ref>{{cite news |title=Muslim Council deplores Wijedasa's statement on ISIS |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Muslim-Council-deplores-Wijedasa-s-statement-on-ISIS/108-119413 |accessdate=22 April 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |location=Sri Lanka |date=19 November 2016 |language=English}}</ref> and was linked in 2018 to vandalism of Buddhist statues following [[2018 anti-Muslim riots in Sri Lanka|anti-Muslim riots in Sri Lanka]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190422-little-known-islamist-group-ntj-accused-sri-lanka-blasts|title=Little-known Islamist group NTJ accused in Sri Lanka blasts|date=22 April 2019|work=France 24|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nearly 190 dead, 500 injured as two more blasts strike Sri Lanka on Easter Sunday |url=https://www.sindhpost.com.pk/nearly-190-dead-500-injured-as-two-more-blasts-strike-sri-lanka-on-easter-sunday/ |accessdate=22 April 2019 |work=Sindh Post |date=21 April 2019}}</ref> NTJ's leader and \"bombing mastermind\" Zahran Hashim from Sri Lanka, preached on a pro-ISIL Sri Lankan [[Facebook]] account, known as \"Al-Ghuraba\" media, and on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Sri Lanka bombings 'retaliation' for Christchurch mosque attacks, minister says |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12224693 |work=NZ Herald |date=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sri Lanka 'bombing mastermind' named as Moulvi Zahran Hashim |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/04/23/sri-lanka-bombing-mastermind-named-moulvi-zahran-hashim/ |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/International/Who-is-Moulvi-Zahran-Hashim-mastermind-of-one-of-the-Sri-Lanka-attacks-587544|title=Unconfirmed reports blame Zahran Hashim for Sri Lanka attack. Who is he? \u2013 World News \u2013 Jerusalem Post|website=www.jpost.com|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Jammiyathul Millathu Ibrahim ===\nDuring a press conference on 23 April 2019, State Defence Minister [[Ruwan Wijewardene]] confirmed that a second [[Schism|splinter]] group was being investigated, but declined to provide details. On 27 April 2019, President Sirisena designated Jammiyathul Millathu Ibrahim (the splinter group) and [[National Thowheeth Jama'ath]] as terrorist organisations. This enables the freezing and seizure of assets belonging to these groups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/President-bans-National-Thawheed-Jammath/108-166074|title=President bans National Thawheed Jammath|website=www.dailymirror.lk|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Foreign Policy 230419\">{{cite web |last1=Mackinnon |first1=Amy |title=Sri Lanka Attack 'Is the Wave of the Future' |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/04/23/sri-lanka-attack-is-the-wave-of-the-future-isis-terrorism-returnees/ |website=Foreign Policy |accessdate=26 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Willayath As Seylani ===\nWillayath As Seylani proscribed among NTJ and JMI under Emergency regulations of 75(1).<ref>{{Citation |title=The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka |date=13 May 2019|volume=Part 1: Section (1) \u2013 General: Government Notifications \u2013 The public Security Ordinance (Chapter 40)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/05/14/everything-you-need-to-know-today-199/|title=Everything you need to know today \u2013 Sri Lanka Latest News|date=14 May 2019|website=Sri Lanka News \u2013 Newsfirst}}</ref>\n\n=== Identities of the bombers ===\nWijewardene announced that most of the suicide bombers were \"well-educated and come from middle or upper-middle class\", and that they were \"financially quite independent\". He stated one of the bombers studied in the United Kingdom before going to Australia to complete a postgraduate degree.<ref name=\"tycoon\">{{cite news|last1=Gettleman|first1=Jeffrey|last2=Bastians|first2=Dharisha|last3=Schultz|first3=Kai|title=Sri Lanka Suicide Bombers Included Two Sons of a Spice Tycoon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/24/world/asia/sri-lanka-bombers-millionaire.html|date=24 April 2019|work=The New York Times|accessdate=25 April 2019|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nSri Lankan police have identified the nine suicide bombers:<ref name=\"bombers\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/05/01/identities-of-easter-sunday-suicide-bombers-revealed-for-the-first-time/|title=Identities of Easter Sunday Suicide bombers revealed for the first time \u2013 Sri Lanka Latest News|date=1 May 2019|website=Sri Lanka News \u2013 Newsfirst}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! No.!! Name !! Native Place !! Location attacked!!Note\n|-\n| 1||Alawdeen Ahmed Muad||[[Mattakkuliya]]|| St. Anthony's Shrine|| His brother has been arrested.<ref name=\"names\">{{Cite web|url=https://economynext.com/Sri_Lanka_names_Easter_suicide_bombers-3-14272.html|title=Sri Lanka names Easter suicide bombers|website=www.economynext.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2||Atchchi Muhammadu Muhammadu Hasthun|| [[Valaichchenai]]|| St.Sebastian's Church||His wife who was identified as Pulasthini Rajendran (Sarah) and wanted by CID over the attacks, was killed during a police raid at a house in Saithamaruthu on 26 April 2019.\n|-\n| 3||Mohamed Nassar Mohamed Asad|| Kattankudy|| Zion Church||Married and aged 27.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news/54662/identity-of-zion-church-bomber-confirmed |title=Identity of Zion Church bomber confirmed}}</ref> He originally targeted [[St. Mary's Cathedral, Batticaloa|St. Mary's Cathedral]] but was dropped off at the Zion Church since mass service had ended when he arrived.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/190428/news/zion-church-bombers-initial-target-was-st-marys-cathedral-347164.html|title=Zion Church bomber's initial target was St. Mary's Cathedral}}</ref>\n|-\n| 4||Mohamed Azam Mohamed Mubarak|| [[Colombo 12]]|| Kingsbury Hotel||Member of NTJ, exploded a bomb at Kingsbury by 9.15 to 9.20 AM.<ref name=\"timeline\" /> His wife has been arrested.<ref name=\"names\" />\n|-\n| 5||Mohamed Cassim Mohamed Zahran|| Kattankudy || Shangri-La Hotel||The founder of NTJ and the suspected ringleader of the attacks, is believed to have been one of the suicide bombers who struck the Shangri-La hotel in Colombo.<ref name=\"founder\">{{cite web |last1=Srivastava |first1=Abhaya |title=Zahran Hashim: Radical Islamist linked to Sri Lanka blasts |url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2019/04/24/zahran-hashim-radical-islamist-linked-to-sri-lanka-blasts.html |website=thejakartapost.com |publisher=AFP |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> His wife and daughter were injured and his father and 2 brothers were killed whilst the police were conducting a breach and clear at a home on 26 April 2019 in Saithamaruthu.\n|-\n| 6||Mohamed Ibrahim Inshaf Ahamed|| Dematagoda || Cinnamon Grand||Aged 33, was the owner of Colossus Copper, a manufacturing facility in Wellampitiya. Investigators believe Inshaf used his factory to fabricate the suicide vests used in the attack, supplying bolts and screws that filled the devices.<ref name=\"Telegraph 240419\" /><ref name=\"tycoon\" /><ref name=\"Firstpost 240419\" /><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web |last1=Brock |first1=Joe |title=Blood brothers: the wealthy family behind Sri Lanka's suicide attacks |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sri-lanka-blasts-bombers/blood-brothers-the-wealthy-family-behind-sri-lankas-suicide-attacks-idUSKCN1S0202 |website=reuters.com |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> His father, brother and wife are currently in the custody of the CID. He is brother of Ilham.\n|-\n| 7||Mohamed Ibrahim Ilham Ahamed|| Dematagoda|| Shangri-La Hotel||Aged 31, younger brother of Inshaf.<ref name=\"CNN 260419\">{{cite news |last1=Sidhu |first1=Sandi |last2=Griffiths |first2=James |title=Sri Lanka bombing suspects may still be on the run, police warn |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/25/asia/sri-lanka-investigation-arrests-intl/index.html |accessdate=26 April 2019 |work=CNN |date=26 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"tycoon\" /> Husband of Fathima who killed herself.\n|-\n| 8||Abdul Lathif Jameel Mohammed|| [[Gampola]]|| Tropical Inn||Aged 36, detonated his bomb at the Tropical Inn. Mohamed had previously studied in the United Kingdom and Australia and may have been radicalized while in Australia. He had originally attempted to bomb the Taj Samudra in Colombo, but his device failed to detonate.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pallin |first1=Megan |title=Sri Lanka bomber 'radicalised in Australia', says sister |url=https://www.news.com.au/world/asia/sri-lanka-bomber-radicalised-in-australia-says-sister/news-story/cb3819bb1536b1043c37c2ceaed4f2f0 |website=news.com.au |publisher=news.com.au |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 9||Fathima Ilham|| -|| Mahawila Gardens||Pregnant wife of Mohamed Ibrahim Ilham Ahamed. She detonated her bomb killing herself and her three sons, and three police officers, in the police raid of her home in [[Dematagoda]].<ref name=\"tycoon\" /><ref name=\"Firstpost 240419\">{{cite web |last1=Swami |first1=Praveen |title=Sri Lanka blasts: Fatima Ibrahim identified as one of the suicide bombers; wife of SL millionaire blew self up with unborn child |url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/sri-lanka-blasts-fatima-ibrahim-identified-as-one-of-the-suicide-bombers-wife-of-sl-millionaire-blew-self-up-with-unborn-child-6508131.html |website=Firstpost |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\" />\n|}\n\n=== Ties to Islamic State ===\n{{Cleanup section|reason=difficult to follow|date=April 2019}}\nThe attackers are assessed to have links with [[Islamic State of Iraq and Levant]], at least in the digital sphere.<ref name=\"autolongwar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2019/04/terrorists-in-sri-lanka-swore-allegiance-to-baghdadi.php|title=Terrorists in Sri Lanka swore allegiance to Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi &#124; FDD's Long War Journal|date=23 April 2019|website=www.longwarjournal.org}}</ref>\n\nHashim was featured in a video released by Amaq purporting to show eight of the suicide bombers.<ref name=\"auto5\" /> One of the bombers, Abdul Latheef, had tried to travel to Syria to join the Islamic State.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sri-lanka-blasts-bomber/the-western-educated-bomber-who-botched-sri-lanka-hotel-attack-idUSKCN1S21PE | title = The Western-educated bomber who botched Sri Lanka hotel attack | author = Alasdair Pal, Shihar Aneez | website = Reuters | access-date = 30 April 2019}}</ref> It was reported that he was one of the subjects of a terrorism investigation by the Australian Joint Counter Terrorism Team in 2014 after intelligence emerged linking him to an IS operative [[Neil Prakash]].<ref>{{cite news |title=One suicide bomber probed by Australia in 2014 |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/One-suicide-bomber-probed-by-Australia-in-2014/108-165951 |accessdate=26 April 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |date=26 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref> British newspaper ''The Times'' has reported that security agencies believe he might have reached Syria where he was trained and had links with British ISIL members like [[Jihadi John]] and [[Junaid Hussain]].<ref name=\"isisreport2019\">{{cite news |title=UK security forces hunt for ISIS 'sleeper cells' after SL blasts: Report |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/uk-security-forces-hunt-for-isis-crocodile-cells-report-119042800390_1.html |accessdate=30 April 2019 |website=Business Standard |date=28 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Sainthamaruthu shootout]], Amaq claimed those killed in the raid were men of ISIL and published a photo which showed Rilwan who had blown himself up.<ref name=\"loyalists\">{{cite web| url = https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2019/04/sri-lankan-security-forces-clash-with-islamic-state-loyalists.php | title = Sri Lankan security forces clash with Islamic State loyalists | date = 27 April 2019 | author = Thomas Joscelyn | website = Long War Journal | access-date = 28 April 2019}}</ref> The other man in the image has been identified to be Zahran.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/04/28/sri-lanka-extremists-warned-attacks-would-follow-video/|title=Sri Lanka extremists warned more attacks would follow in video|first=Qadijah|last=Irshad|date=28 April 2019|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> Islamic State also released a video purportedly showing their leader [[Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi]] praising the attackers and claiming the attacks were revenge for the loss of Baghouz in Syria.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://fortune.com/2019/04/29/isis-abu-bakr-al-baghdadi-video/ | title = Man Said to Be Islamic State Leader Calls Sri Lanka Bombings Revenge | author = Dana Kharachie | website = Fortune | access-date = 30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nBased on their early probe, the investigators have said that the attack was planned locally without any direct hand of Islamic State. Zahran once made his cohorts listen to a recording of a puproprted ISIS official making him the head of the Sri Lankan branch. But they believe he lied greatly to others about the extent of his contacts with the group. General [[Mahesh Senanayake]] said the attackers utilised the ideology of Islamic State so it could get the blame.<ref name=\"Pledge\">{{cite news| url = https://www.business-standard.com/article/international/blew-up-motorcycles-lost-fingers-how-lanka-bombers-trained-for-the-attack-119050600220_1.html | title = Blew up motorcycles, lost fingers: How Lanka bombers trained for the attack | author = Saeed Shah and Bill Spindle | website = Business Standard | access-date = 29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nRavi Seneviratne, the DIG who leads the [[Criminal Investigation Department (Sri Lanka)|Criminal Investigation Department]], testified in July that they had no evidence of the group having a direct involvement. Seneviratne added that the NTJ was inspired by its ideology, but its members had convinced the group through Indonesian intermediaries to take responsibility two days after the attacks.<ref name=\"Ravi\">{{cite news| url = http://www.adaderana.lk/news/56616/no-evidence-that-is-was-behind-easter-attacks-senior-dig-ravi-seneviratne | title = No evidence that IS was behind Easter attacks \u2013 Senior DIG Ravi Seneviratne | website = ADA Derana | access-date = 20 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n=== Political ===\n{{See also|2018 Sri Lankan constitutional crisis|2019 Sri Lankan presidential election}}\nThe [[Inspector General of Police (Sri Lanka)|Inspector General of Police]], [[Pujith Jayasundara]], came under heavy criticism, following the bombings, with the [[United People's Freedom Alliance]] urging that he resign for this total failure to prevent the bombings.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/04/22/upfa-urges-igp-to-resign-immediately/|title=UPFA urges IGP to resign immediately|date=22 April 2019|website= newsfirst |access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref> Later, former Presidential candidate Field Marshal [[Sarath Fonseka]] claimed it was unfair to blame the IGP and claimed it was a conflict between the functioning of military intelligence and criminal investigators, and called for better intelligence mechanisms and security clearances to be streamlined.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Terror-attack:-Not-fair-to-blame-IGP:-SF/108-165820|title=Terror attack: Not fair to blame IGP: SF|date=23 April 2019|website= Dailymirror |access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a speech delivered in parliament, former president and current opposition leader [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] slammed the government for weakening the intelligence services over the years. He stated that in January 2015, he handed over a secure and peaceful country with a strong national security apparatus. He claimed the present government is squarely responsible for the 2019 Easter bombings, stating that on an important occasion such as Easter, representatives of the government usually attend Mass; on this occasion, no representatives were present in or near churches. He blamed the government for diluting the powers of the national security apparatus and claimed this terrorist attack would never have occurred under his administration. Additionally, the government was preparing to repeal the [[Prevention of Terrorism Act (Sri Lanka)|Prevention of Terrorism Act]]; he questioned what kind of position the government would have been in to respond to the incident had they been successful in having the Act repealed.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/MR-blasts-govt--for-diluting-intelligence-services/108-165806|title=MR blasts govt. for diluting intelligence services|date=23 April 2019|website= Dailymirror |access-date=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 April 2019, President [[Maithripala Sirisena|Sirisena]] promised major changes to the leadership of the security forces within the next 24 hours and pledged a \"complete restructure\" of the police and national security forces in the coming weeks. These changes come amidst allegations that a rift between the President and Prime Minister contributed to the failure to effectively respond to threats that undermine national security. The incident also caused a major setback for the government and for other political parties just before [[2019 Sri Lankan presidential election]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/04/sri-lankan-president-vows-security-shake-attacks-190423175114094.html|title=Sri Lankan president vows security shake-up over attacks|date=24 April 2019|website=[[Al Jazeera]]|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nCabinet Spokesman [[Rajitha Senaratne]] initially attempted to implicate [[Gotabaya Rajapaksa]] for the bombings, claiming that [[Abdul Razik]] was a suicide bomber and the secretary of the NTJ that received funding from intelligence agencies during the Rajapaksa government. Razik however is the general secretary of the Ceylon Thowheed Jama\u2019ath (CTJ), one of the splinter groups from Sri Lanka Thawheed Jama\u2019ath (SLTJ) of which he was the former general secretary and is neither a member of the NTJ nor a suicide bomber. Razik challenged Rajitha to provide evidence for the allegations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/04/30/gota-supported-organizations-such-as-ntj-rajitha-senaratne/|title=\"Gota supported organizations such as NTJ\" \u2013 Rajitha Senaratne \u2013 Sri Lanka Latest News|date=30 April 2019|website=Sri Lanka News \u2013 Newsfirst|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ft.lk/news/Ban-on-face-veil-acceptable--but-ears-must-be-covered--Ceylon-Thowheed-Jama-ath/56-677520|title=Ban on face veil acceptable, but ears must be covered: Ceylon Thowheed Jama'ath|website=www.ft.lk|language=English|access-date=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nPrime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe later apologised for failing to stop the attacks, issuing a statement on Twitter saying \"We take collective responsibility and apologise to our fellow citizens for our failure to protect victims of these tragic events. We pledge to rebuild our churches, revive our economy, and take all measures to prevent terrorism, with the support of the international community.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/we-apologise-to-our-fellow-citizens-says-sri-lanka-pm-ranil-wickremesinghe-on-easter-sunday-blasts-2029285|title=\"We Apologise To Our Fellow Citizens\": Lankan PM on Easter Sunday Blasts|website=NDTV.com|access-date=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nPresident [[Maithripala Sirisena]] attempted to connect International drug syndicates to the bombings to justify his campaign to implement the death penalty to drug dealers but Prime Minister [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]] discounted the president's claims.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sri Lanka President claims drug gangs orchestrated Easter blasts |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/south-asia/sri-lanka-president-claims-drug-gangs-orchestrated-easter-blasts/articleshow/70237163.cms |website=Times of India (TOI) |publisher=TOI |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/sri-lanka-president-death-penalty-drugs-convicts-11662920|title=Sri Lanka president signs death warrants for four drug convicts to end 43-year moratorium|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=26 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_19A/Jul01_1561970690CH.php|title=Sri Lanka : Sri Lanka President claims drug traffickers are behind the Easter Sunday bomb attacks|website=www.colombopage.com|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== 2019 Sri Lankan Presidential Election ====\nIn November 2019, [[Gotabaya Rajapaksa]] was elected President who campaigned on stronger security measures to prevent a re-occurrence of the Easter bombings.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Athas |first1=Iqbal |title=Sri Lanka elects new president in first vote since deadly bombings |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/17/asia/sri-lanka-election-intl/index.html |accessdate=20 November 2019 |agency=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\n==== Resignations ====\n;Defence Secretary\nOn 23 April, President Sirisena announced plans to change the heads of the [[Sri Lanka Armed Forces|defence forces]].<ref name=\"Reuters 230419\" /> On 25 April, [[Hemasiri Fernando]], [[Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka)#Permanent Secretaries|Secretary of the Ministry of Defence]] tendered his resignation to the President, after it was announced that President Sirisena had requested the Defence Secretary and the Inspector General of Police resign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/top_story/Prez-tells-Defence-Secretary--IGP-to-resign/155-165882|title=Prez tells Defence Secretary, IGP to resign|website=www.dailymirror.lk|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref> Retired [[General]] [[Shantha Kottegoda]] was appointed to succeed Fernando as Secretary of the Ministry of Defence, while retired IGP [[N. K. Illangakoon]] was appointed adviser to the Ministry of Defence.\n\n;Inspector General of Police\nAlthough President Sirisena announced on 25 April that the [[Inspector General of Police]], [[Pujith Jayasundara]] would be resigning, Jayasundara made no public comment. On 29 April, the IGP was sent on compulsory leave after no response was received to President Sirisena's request for his resignation. The President lacks jurisdiction to dismiss the IGP, as he was appointed by a decision by the Constitutional Council and can only be removed by a motion passed in Parliament pursuant to the Public Officers (Procedure) Act, which requires the precise circumstances of the charges and/or allegations against him to be detailed and presented. The Police Commission still maintains jurisdiction to overturn the decision to send the IGP on compulsory leave.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/I-can\u2019t-remove-IGP--he-is-a-CC-appointee:-Prez/108-165827|title=I can't remove IGP, he is a CC appointee: Prez|website=www.dailymirror.lk}}</ref> The same day, Senior Deputy Inspector General of Police [[C. D. Wickramaratne]] was appointed as the Acting Inspector General of Police<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2019/04/30/local/184227/igp-sent-compulsory-leave|title=IGP sent on Compulsory Leave|first=Camelia|last=Nathaniel|website=Daily News}}</ref> and [[General]] [[Shantha Kottegoda]] was appointed Defence Secretary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.lk/front-page/Kottegoda-new-Defence-Secretary/44-677294|title=Kottegoda new Defence Secretary|website=www.ft.lk}}</ref> On 13 May, the [[Constitutional Council (Sri Lanka)|Constitutional Council]] endorsed the appointment of C. D. Wickramaratne as Acting IGP. This is considered final and conclusive for all purposes, as neither the National Police Commission or the Supreme Court have jurisdictional oversight to reverse this decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/CC-approves-C-D--Wickramaratne-as-Acting-IGP/108-167023|title=CC approves C.D. Wickramaratne as Acting IGP|website=www.dailymirror.lk|accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nPujith Jayasundara has since challenged his compulsory leave with a petition to the [[Supreme Court of Sri Lanka|Supreme Court]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.colombotelegraph.com/index.php/easter-attack-igp-pujith-jayasundaras-fr-petition-against-sending-him-on-compulsory-leave-full-text/|title=Easter Attack: IGP Pujith Jayasundara's FR Petition Against Sending Him on Compulsory Leave \u2013 Full Text|date=4 June 2019}}</ref> On 2 July, the former police chief along with the former defence official were arrested according to the order by the President and the current Attorney General [[Dappula de Livera]] over the alleged security lapses which lead to the attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/07/sri-lanka-police-chief-arrested-easter-attacks-failures-190702114713818.html|title=Sri Lanka police chief arrested over Easter attacks failures|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> They were arrested while being hospitalised and are charged for the crimes against humanity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_19A/Jul02_1562072919CH.php|title=Sri Lanka : Sri Lanka Police Chief and former Defense secretary arrested over failure to prevent Easter Sunday Attacks|website=www.colombopage.com|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Ministers and Provincial Governors \nFollowing calls for resignation of Minister of Industry and Commerce, [[Rishad Bathiudeen]] and Proven\u00e7al Governors [[Azath Salley]] and [[M. L. A. M. Hizbullah]]; including a fast carried-out by Member of Parliament, [[Venerable]] [[Athuraliye Rathana Thero]], [[List of Governors of Western Province|Governor of Western Province]] Azath Salley and [[List of Governors of Eastern Province|Governor of Eastern Province]] M. L. A. M. Hizbullah tendered their resignations to President Sirisena on 3 June, who had appointed both in January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Rathana-Thera-ends-fast/108-168558|title=Rathana Thera ends fast|website=www.dailymirror.lk}}</ref> This was followed the same day by an announcement by [[Rauff Hakeem]], Leader of the [[Sri Lanka Muslim Congress]] stating that all Muslim Ministers will resign from their portfolios to \"to facilitate investigations to be conducted in a free and fair manner\". This included cabinet ministers [[Kabir Hashim]], [[Rauff Hakeem]], [[M.H.A. Haleem]] and [[Rishad Bathiudeen]]; state ministers [[Faizal Cassim]], [[H. M. M. Harees]], [[Ameer Ali Shihabdeen]] and [[Seyed Ali Zahir Moulana]] and Deputy Minister [[Abdullah Mahrooff]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/All-Muslim-ministers-decide-to-resign/108-168564|title=All Muslim ministers decide to resign|website=www.dailymirror.lk}}</ref> On 4 June, former [[Mayor of Colombo]], [[A. J. M. Muzammil]] was appointed Governor of Western Province by President Sirisena succeeding Salley.\n\n;Chief of National Intelligence\n[[Sisira Mendis]], [[Chief of National Intelligence]] (CNI) resigned citing health reasons, on 8 June 2019, days after giving testimony that the Parliamentary Select Committee to inquire into the Easter bombings which had outraged President Sirisena.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://colombogazette.com/2019/06/08/chief-of-national-intelligence-sisira-mendis-resigns/|title=Chief of National Intelligence Sisira Mendis resigns|date=8 June 2019}}</ref> He was succeeded by Major General [[Jeewaka Ruwan Kulatunga]] as CNI.\n\n=== Economic ===\n[[Tourism in Sri Lanka]] is the country's third largest foreign exchange earner and employs around 135,000 to 150,000 in the hotel industry. The industry had expected 3 million tourist arrivals and revenue of $5 billion in 2019. Due to the attack on tourists, The Hotels Association of Sri Lanka estimated a loss of $1.5 billion in tourism earnings for the year.<ref name=\"ft 250419\">{{cite web |last1=de Silva |first1=Charumini |title=Tourist hotels fear $1.5 b revenue loss from terror attacks |url=http://www.ft.lk/front-page/Tourist-hotels-fear----1-5-b-revenue-loss-from-terror-attacks/44-676993 |website=www.ft.lk |accessdate=26 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nThe government's plan to grant visa-on-arrival to visitors from 39 countries has been suspended due to the current security situation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sri Lanka cancels visa-on-arrival for 39 countries in the wake of Easter blasts |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/travel/destinations/sri-lanka-cancels-visa-on-arrival-for-39-countries-in-the-wake-of-easter-blasts/as69054524.cms |website=Times of India Travel |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn early June, in a leaked confidential assessment of the economic damage by the Easter Sunday attacks, the [[Central Bank of Sri Lanka]] claimed that the loss of government revenue from indirect tax such as [[VAT]] was approximately Rupees 26 billion for the year. It cited major impact on the country's trade deficit of the balance of payments, which would be affected badly due to the negative impact on tourism. It stated further that many foreign direct investments have been postponed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Loss-from-VAT--NBT-to-reach-Rs-26bn-by-year-end:-CBSL/108-168608|title=Loss from VAT, NBT to reach Rs. 26bn by year end: CBSL|website=www.dailymirror.lk}}</ref>\n\nDespite the downfall in number of foreign tourist arrivals following the Easter Sunday attacks, as of July 2019 Sri Lanka still continues to be the [[Lonely Planet]]'s top destination for 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_19A/Jul03_1562134322CH.php|title=Sri Lanka : Sri Lanka still Lonely Planet\\'s top destination for 2019 despite Easter Sunday attacks|website=www.colombopage.com|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lonelyplanet.com/sri-lanka/travel-tips-and-articles/why-i-wont-give-up-on-sri-lanka-and-you-shouldnt-either/40625c8c-8a11-5710-a052-1479d2750f63|title=Why I won't give up on Sri Lanka and you shouldn't either|last=Planet|first=Lonely|date=29 June 2019|website=Lonely Planet|language=en|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> Consequently, Sri Lanka was promoted as the upper middle income earning country from being a lower middle income earning country according to the updated classification of the [[World Bank]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/07/02/sri-lankas-gross-national-income-increases/|title=Sri Lanka's Gross National Income increases \u2013 Sri Lanka Latest News|date=2 July 2019|website=Sri Lanka News \u2013 Newsfirst|language=en|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> The Sri Lankan hotel sector is in rebuilding process and on the verge of returning to normalcy with tourist arrivals started to increase in June faster than expected following the attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economynext.com/Sri_Lanka_tourist_arrivals_starting_to_recover_in_June-3-15000-7.html|title=Sri Lanka tourist arrivals starting to recover in June|website=www.economynext.com|language=en|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economynext.com/Sri_Lanka_hotel_stocks_rise_as_tourism_recovers_faster_than_expected,_rupee_gains-3-15004.html|title=Sri Lanka hotel stocks rise as tourism recovers faster than expected, rupee gains|website=www.economynext.com|language=en|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Social ===\nGovernment Minister [[Patali Champika Ranawaka]] called for the [[Batticaloa Campus]] and Islamic study centres in Beruwala, Maharagama, Tincomalee and Addalachchenai to be brought under the control and supervision of the [[University Grants Commission (Sri Lanka)|University Grants Commission]] and the Education Ministry.<ref>{{cite news |title=Champika proposes action plan to counter fundamentalist terrorism |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Champika-proposes-action-plan-to-counter-fundamentalist-terrorism/108-165969 |accessdate=26 April 2019 |work=Daily Mirror |date=26 April 2019 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 April 2019, [[Sri Lanka Cricket]] called off an under-19 tour of the country by the Pakistan cricket team, scheduled to take place in May, saying \"we didn't want to take any chances\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Farooq |first1=Umar |title=Pakistan's Under-19 tour of Sri Lanka called off |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26615762/pakistan-19-tour-sri-lanka-called-off |accessdate=27 April 2019 |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=27 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the attacks, thousands of Sri Lankans bought [[terrorism insurance]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Thousands of Sri Lankans grab terrorism insurance the week after bombings |url=https://economynext.com/Thousands_of_Sri_Lankans_grab_terrorism_insurance_the_week_after_bombings-3-14279-17.html |website=www.economynext.com |accessdate=2 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIslamic channel [[Peace TV]], which is run by preacher and televangelist [[Zakir Naik]], was officially banned in the country by the main satellite cable operators [[Dialog TV]], [[PEO TV]] and Lanka Broadband Network following the attacks even before the governmental intervention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/474539|title=After Sri Lanka bombings, Zakir's Peace TV 'blocked' by cable companies|date=1 May 2019|website=Malaysiakini|language=en|access-date=3 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/international/cable-operators-in-lanka-block-zakir-naiks-peace-tv-731641.html|title=Cable operators in Lanka block Zakir Naik's Peace TV|date=1 May 2019|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=3 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Legislative ===\nFollowing the attack, calls have been made to introduce legislation to prevent possible future occurrence of such attacks. The government called for the swift enactment of the proposed ''Counter Terrorism Act,'' replacing the existing ''Prevention of Terrorism Act''.\n\n==== Regulation of madrasas ====\nThe Ministry for Muslim Religious and Cultural Affairs has proposed the ''Madrasa Education Regulatory Act'' to establish a Board under the Ministry for ''\"regulation, registration, supervision, control and development of education within [[Madrasa]]s in Sri Lanka\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/190512/news/new-laws-to-regulate-madrasas-introduced-by-muslim-affairs-ministry-349012.html|title=New laws to regulate Madrasas; introduced by Muslim Affairs Ministry}}</ref>\n\n==== Sharia law ====\nMinister of Home Affairs [[Vajira Abeywardena]] stated that legislation introduced between 2010 and 2015 has \"given effect to aspects of Sharia law or Islamic law\" with non-governmental organisations registering under these. He stated that these parliamentary acts will be reviewed.<ref name=\"DM27052019\">[\nhttp://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Govt--to-revise-laws-giving-effect-to-Sharia-%E2%80%93-Vajira/108-167920 Govt. to revise laws giving effect to Sharia \u2013 Vajira]</ref>\n\n==== Public signage ====\nThe government has stated that the Ministry of Home Affairs will issue a circular calling for the removal of all signage displayed in the Arabic language. This follows a statement by the Prime Minister which stated that all street name boards in the island should only be in [[Sinhala language|Sinhalese]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[English language|English]].<ref>[http://www.adaderana.lk/news.php?nid=55331 Circular to be issued calling for removal of name boards in Arabic \u2013 Vajira]</ref>\n\n==== Minimum age of marriage ====\nThe Prime Minister has stated that the ''Muslim Marriage and Divorce Act'' will be amended to include a minimum age of marriage of 18 years to the [[Muslim law in Sri Lanka|traditional Muslim law]], which had been criticised for lacking a minimum age of marriage, resulting in underage marriages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-39898589|title=Forced to marry at 15|date=20 June 2017|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Govt--to-amend-Muslim-Marriage-and-Divorce-Act/108-167849|title=Govt. to amend Muslim Marriage and Divorce Act|website=www.dailymirror.lk}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports ===\n==== Association football ====\nThe [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC First Round|2022 FIFA World Cup qualifying campaign]] 2nd leg clash between [[Sri Lanka national football team|Sri Lanka]] and [[Macau national football team|Macau]] was unable to take part as the Macanese squad refused to travel to Sri Lanka amidst the concern after the Easter bombings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thetelegram.com/sports/world-cup-qualifier-in-sri-lanka-canceled-after-macau-refuse-to-travel-320518/|title=World Cup qualifier in Sri Lanka canceled after Macau refuse to travel &#124; The Telegram|first=Reuters|last=Inc|website=www.thetelegram.com}}</ref> [[FIFA]] subsequently forfeited the match and awarded a 3\u20130 win to Sri Lanka, thus qualified the team to the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC Second Round|second round]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2019/06/29/sri-lanka-welcomes-fifa-ruling-macau-out-of-wcup-qualifying/39638659/|title=Sri Lanka welcomes FIFA ruling Macau out of WCup qualifying|website=USA TODAY}}</ref>\n\n== Reactions ==\n=== Domestic responses ===\nLeaders of the country condemned the attacks: President [[Maithripala Sirisena]] said \"I have given instructions to take very stern action against the persons who are responsible for this conspiracy\";<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_19A/Apr21_1555832583CH.php|title=Sri Lanka President condemns 'dastardly' attack, calls for restraint and patience|date=21 April 2019|website=ColomboPage|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> the Prime Minister [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]] said \"I strongly condemn the cowardly attacks on our people today\";<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/sri-lanka-prime-minister-condemns-cowardly-attacks-11464980|title=Sri Lanka blasts: Prime minister condemns 'cowardly' attacks|date=21 April 2019|website=CNA |access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref> [[Leader of the Opposition (Sri Lanka)|Opposition Leader]] and former President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] called the attacks \"absolutely barbaric\" and said that the nation will stand united as one against \"acts of terrorism\";<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/south-asia/berlin-horrified-by-sri-lanka-blasts-targeting-churches-hotels|title=Sri Lanka explosions: Ex-president Mahinda Rajapaksa and other world leaders condemn attacks|date=21 April 2019|website=The Straits Times|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> and Finance Minister [[Mangala Samaraweera]] described the attacks as a \"well co-ordinated attempt to create murder, mayhem and anarchy\".<ref name=\"bbc-21apr2019\" />\n\nThe Roman Catholic Archbishop of Colombo, [[Malcolm Ranjith|Cardinal Malcolm Ranjith]], said \"It\u2019s a very very sad day for all of us. I wish therefore to express my deepest sorrow and sympathy [...] I condemn to the utmost of my capacity this act that has caused so much death and suffering to the people.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2019/apr/21/sri-lanka-explosions-dozens-killed-and-hundreds-injured-in-church-and-hotel-blasts?page=with%3Ablock-5cbc29e58f08c89bd906580d|title=Sri Lanka attacks: seven arrested after 207 killed at hotels and churches on Easter Sunday&nbsp;\u2013 live|last1=Siddique (now)|first1=Haroon|last2=Rourke (earlier)|first2=Alison|date=21 April 2019|via=The guardian|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> Following the attack, the Archbishop's House in Colombo cancelled all Catholic [[Easter]] services planned for the evening of Easter Sunday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hirunews.lk/|title=Hiru News |accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April 2019 a public litigation activist, [[Nagananda Kodituwakku]], stated that the negligence leading to the attack is in violation of the [[Penal Code of Sri Lanka|Penal Code]] and the Criminal Procedure Code and has filed a [[Fundamental rights|Fundamental Rights petition]] directing the [[Attorney general|Attorney General]] to institute criminal action against the country's senior political, civil and security officials, including President [[Maithripala Sirisena]] and former President and MP [[Mahinda Rajapaksa|Mahinda Rajapakse]], for their alleged negligence over the Easter Sunday bombings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2019/04/29/law-order/184126/fr-filed-over-easter-bomb-blasts|title=FR filed over Easter bomb blasts|last=Sooriyagoda|first=Lakmal|website=Daily News|language=en|access-date=19 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hirunews.lk/215384/a-supreme-court-petition-against-the-government-for-its-failure-to-prevent-terrorist-attacks|title=A Supreme Court petition against the Government for its failure to prevent terrorist attacks|website=Hiru News|language=en|access-date=19 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== International responses ===\nNumerous world leaders expressed condolences and condemnation.{{efn|World leaders giving condolences included those of Afghanistan,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-04/21/c_137996044.htm|title=Afghanistan condemns serial blasts in Sri Lanka|date=21 April 2019|work=[[Xinhua]]|access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref> Australia,<ref>{{cite news|first=Perry|last=Duffin|title=Scott Morrison and Bill Shorten condemn Sri Lanka bombings|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6082270/innocent-lives-have-been-stolen-australian-leaders-condemn-sri-lanka-bombings/|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=21 April 2019|access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref> Bangladesh,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailystar.net/country/news/pm-president-condemn-sri-lanka-attack-express-condolences-1732891|title=PM, President condemn Sri Lanka attack, express condolences |date= 21 April 2019|website=The Daily Star |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190421085640/https://www.thedailystar.net/country/news/pm-president-condemn-sri-lanka-attack-express-condolences-1732891 |archive-date=21 April 2019 |access-date= 21 April 2019}}</ref> Brazil,<ref>{{cite web | work = O antagonista |url= https://www.oantagonista.com/brasil/bolsonaro-condena-atentado-no-sri-lanka/|title=Bolsonaro condena atentado no Sri Lanka}}</ref> Brunei,<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.mfa.gov.bn/Lists/Press%20Room/news.aspx?id=751&source=http://www.mfa.gov.bn/site/home.aspx |title=Message of condolence to the Prime Minister of the Democratic Socialist of Sri Lanka on the recent bomb attacks |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Brunei)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Brunei]] |date=23 April 2019 |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref> Bulgaria,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://focus-news.net/news/2019/04/21/2649330/premierat-boyko-borisov-izprati-saboleznovatelna-telegrama-do-ministar-predsedatelya-na-shri-lanka-ranil-vikremesinghe.html |title= Prime Minister Boyko Borisov expressed condolences to Sri Lanka Prime Minister| work = Focus |date=21 April 2019|accessdate= 21 April 2019}}</ref> Cambodia,<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.mfaic.gov.kh/site/detail/29619 |title=Statement of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation on the horrible attacks on churches and hotels in Sri Lanka on 21 April 2019 |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation (Cambodia)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation, Cambodia]] |date=22 April 2019 |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref> Canada,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://globalnews.ca/news/5188243/global-affairs-canadians-sri-lanka/|title=Canadians in Sri Lanka warned more attacks possible after deadly bombings|publisher=Global News|date=21 April 2019|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> China,<ref>{{cw|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-04/22/c_137996394.htm |title=Chinese president, premier send condolence messages to Sri Lanka over deadly attacks |website=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=22 April 2019 |accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref> Denmark,<ref>{{cite news | first=M.L. | last=Norup | url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/udland/udenrigsministeriet-forlydender-om-draebte-og-saarede-danskere-i-sri-lanka | title=Udenrigsministeriet: Forlydender om dr\u00e6bte og s\u00e5rede danskere i Sri Lanka |trans-title=Foreign Ministry: Information about Danish citizens killed and wounded in Sri Lanka |publisher=[[DR (broadcaster)|DR News]]|language=da|date=21 April 2019|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> Finland,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.talouselama.fi/uutiset/te/2bce9a8f-b9f5-4913-9c25-16b2e778950d?|title=Juha Sipil\u00e4 tuomitsee Sri Lankassa p\u00e4\u00e4si\u00e4issunnuntaina tehdyt iskut|publisher=Talousel\u00e4m\u00e4|date=21 April 2019|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> the Holy See,<ref name=\"VaticanNewsWatkins2019\">{{cite news |last1=Watkins |first1=Devin |title=Pope Francis laments Easter Sunday attacks in Sri Lanka |url=https://www.vaticannews.va/en/pope/news/2019-04/pope-francis-laments-sri-lanka-attacks-on-easter.html |accessdate=21 April 2019 |work=Vatican News |date=21 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Hungary,<ref>{{cite web |title= A k\u00fcl\u00fcgyminiszt\u00e9rium el\u00edt\u00e9li a t\u00e1mad\u00e1sokat |trans-title=The Ministry of Foreign Affairs Condemns the Attacks |url= https://magyarnemzet.hu/belfold/a-kulugyminiszterium-eliteli-a-tamadasokat-6807635/ |website= [[Magyar Nemzet]] |accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> India,<ref name=\"ndtv\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/sri-lanka-blasts-pm-narendra-modi-says-no-place-for-such-barbarism-in-our-region-2026295 |title=\"No Place For Such Barbarism in Our Region\": PM Modi on Sri Lanka Blasts |website= NDTV |access-date= 21 April 2019}}</ref> Indonesia,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.antaranews.com/berita/838652/indonesia-kecam-keras-pengeboman-di-sri-lanka|title=Indonesia kecam keras pengeboman di Sri Lanka |website= Antara News |accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> Iran,<ref>{{cite web |title= Sri Lanka's bloody day: Hundreds of casualties in attacks on churches, hotels |url=https://www.presstv.com/Detail/2019/04/21/593945/Sri-Lanka-blasts-massive-casualties|website= [[Press TV]] |accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> Israel,<ref name=israelaid>{{cite web |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-offers-aid-to-sri-lanka-in-call-after-devastating-bombings/ |title=Israel offers aid to Sri Lanka in call after devastating bombings |newspaper=The Times of Israel|date= 21 April 2019}}</ref> Italy,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.rainews.it/dl/rainews/articoli/Sri-Lanka-Mattarella-condanna-gesto-vile-Conte-addolorato-da-deriva-odio-c9cb437a-4cb8-48ec-ab19-19055d6cabce.html |title=Sri Lanka, Mattarella: \"Condanna vile gesto violenza\". Conte: \"Addolorato da nuova deriva d'odio\" |website=RaiNews|language= it|access-date= 21 April 2019}}</ref> Japan,<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.mofa.go.jp/s_sa/sw/lk/page4e_001008.html |title=Message of condolences from Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to Hon. Ranil Wickremesinghe, Prime Minister of Sri Lanka following the terrorist attacks in the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Japan]] |date=22 April 2019 |accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref> Laos,<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.mofa.gov.la/index.php/activities/messages/3167-condolence-message-about-the-string-of-bombings-in-the-catholic-churches-and-hotels-in-sri-lanka-on-21-april-2019 |title=Condolence Message about the string of bombings in the Catholic Churches and Hotels in Sri Lanka on 21 April 2019 |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Laos)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Laos]] |date=23 April 2019 |accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref> Lebanon,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.almanar.com.lb/721536|title=Hezbollah Denounces Sri Lanka Blasts, Hopes Imminent Apparition of Imam Mahdi (P) to Restore World's Security & Peace \u2013 Al-Manar TV Lebanon|website=english.almanar.com.lb}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://colombogazette.com/2019/04/22/hezbollah-condemns-savage-attack-in-sri-lanka/|title=Hezbollah condemns \"savage\" attack in Sri Lanka|last=admin|date=22 April 2019}}</ref> Malaysia,<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.kln.gov.my/web/guest/-/press-release-explosions-in-colombo-sri-lanka |title=Explosions in Colombo, Sri Lanka |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Malaysia]] |date=21 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> Morocco,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2019/04/271242/king-mohammed-vi-sends-condolences-to-sri-lankan-president/ |title=King Mohammed VI Sends Condolences to Sri Lankan President|date=22 April 2019 |accessdate= 22 April 2019|via= Morocco World News}}</ref> New Zealand,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12224177 |title=Sri Lanka explosions: Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern labels attacks 'devastating' and sends NZ's condolences to grieving country|date=21 April 2019 |accessdate= 21 April 2019|via= NZ Herald}}</ref> Pakistan,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.khaleejtimes.com/international/pakistan/pakistan-pm-imran-khan-reacts-to-sri-lanka-church-blasts|title=Prime Minister Imran Khan expresses his condolences to attacks in Sri Lanka |date=21 April 2019 |website= Khaleej times |access-date= 21 April 2019}}</ref> Palestine,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://english.wafa.ps/page.aspx?id=14LSdda110143519431a14LSdd|title=President Abbas condemns Sri Lanka terror attacks|website= [[Wafa]]|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hamas.ps/en/post/2057/press-release-on-terror-attacks-in-sri-lanka|title=Press release on terror attacks in Sri Lanka|website=hamas.ps|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> the Philippines,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Parrocha |first1=Azer |title=Palace sympathizes with families of Sri Lanka blast victims |url= https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1067726 |website=Philippine News Agency |publisher=Philippine Government |accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> Poland,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wiadomosci.wp.pl/sri-lanka-msz-wydalo-oswiadczenie-ws-zamachow-6372716892465281a|title=Sri Lanka. MSZ wyda\u0142o o\u015bwiadczenie ws. zamach\u00f3w|date=21 April 2019|website=[[Wirtualna Polska]]|language=pl|access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref> Portugal,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://24.sapo.pt/atualidade/artigos/antonio-costa-expressa-grande-pesar-pela-morte-de-portugues-no-sri-lanka|title=Ant\u00f3nio Costa expressa \"grande pesar\" pela morte de portugu\u00eas no Sri Lanka|website=[[SAPO (company)|SAPO]]|access-date= 23 April 2019}}</ref> Romania,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://adevarul.ro/news/politica/reactia-presedintelui-iohannis-exploziile-sri-lanka-1_5cbc4705445219c57ecb06a5/index.html |title=Reac\u021bia pre\u0219edintelui Iohannis dup\u0103 exploziile din Sri Lanka |work=Adev\u0103rul |author=Ion Gaidau |date=21 April 2019 |language=Romanian}}</ref> Russia,<ref>{{cw|url=http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/60337|title=Condolences to Sri Lanka President Maithripala Sirisena |publisher=Russian Presidential Executive Office |date=21 April 2019}}</ref> Saudi Arabia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spa.gov.sa/viewstory.php?lang=en&newsid=1915554|title=Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques Sends Cable of Condolence to Sri Lanka's President on Victims of Terrorist Attacks|access-date=23 April 2019}}</ref> Serbia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtv.rs/sr_ci/svet/krvavi-uskrs-u-srilanci-189-mrtvih-560-povredjeno-u-nekoliko-eksplozija_1011022.html|title=\u041a\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0432\u0438 \u0423\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0441 \u0443 \u0428\u0440\u0438 \u041b\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438: \u0421\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043c \u0443\u0445\u0430\u043f\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0445, 207 \u043f\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043d\u0443\u043b\u0438\u0445, 450 \u0440\u0430\u045a\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0445|language=sr|trans-title=Bloody Easter in Sri Lanka: Seven arrested, 207 dead, 450 wounded|access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref> Singapore,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/sri-lanka-blasts-pm-lee-condemns-terror-attacks-casualties-11465134|title=Sri Lanka blasts: PM Lee condemns 'heinous attacks', MFA says no Singaporean casualties|website= CNA |access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref> Slovakia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teraz.sk/spravy/prezident-sr-vyjadril-sustrast-rodina/391157-clanok.html|title=Prezident Kiska vyjadril s\u00fastras\u0165 rodin\u00e1m obet\u00ed v\u00fdbuchov na Sr\u00ed Lanke |date=21 April 2019|website=Teraz |language= sk|access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref> South Korea,<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.mofa.go.kr/eng/brd/m_5676/view.do?seq=320478&srchFr=&amp;srchTo=&amp;srchWord=&amp;srchTp=&amp;multi_itm_seq=0&amp;itm_seq_1=0&amp;itm_seq_2=0&amp;company_cd=&amp;company_nm=&page=1&titleNm= |title=MOFA Spokesperson's Statement on Bombing Attacks in Sri Lanka |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (South Korea)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs, South Korea]] |date=22 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> Thailand,<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.mfa.go.th/main/en/news3/6886/102054-Messages-of-Condolence-from-the-Prime-Minister-of.html |title=Press Release : Messages of Condolence from the Prime Minister of Thailand and the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Thailand on the Bombings in Sri Lanka on 21 April 2019 |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Thailand)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Thailand]] |date=22 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> the United Arab Emirates,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.khaleejtimes.com/news/government/uae-denounces-terrorist-attacks-in-sri-lanka| title=UAE denounces terrorist attacks in Sri Lanka|date=21 April 2019|website=Khaleej Times|access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref> the United Kingdom,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=theresa_may |author=Theresa May |number=1119881548373868544|date = 21 April 2019 |title=The acts of violence against churches and hotels in Sri Lanka are truly appalling, and my deepest sympathies go out to all of those affected at this tragic time. We must stand together to make sure that no one should ever have to practise their faith in fear.}}</ref> the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/reaction-to-sri-lanka-attacks-/4884863.html| title=World Leaders React to Sri Lanka Explosions|date=21 April 2019|website=voanews.com|access-date=22 April 2019}}</ref> Venezuela,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/jaarreaza/status/1120076222518706176|title=El gobierno del presidente Nicol\u00e1s Maduro expresa su profunda condena a los ataques terroristas ocurridos en la Rep\u00fablica Democr\u00e1tica Socialista de Sri Lanka. Venezuela repudia el terrorismo en cualquiera de sus formas y expresa sus m\u00e1s sentidas condolencias/gGb0bmoDn7|first=Jorge Arreaza|last=M|date=21 April 2019|accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/jguaido/status/1120052877282742272|title=Desde Venezuela lamentamos los despreciables hechos terroristas ocurridos en Sri Lanka que dejaron innumerables v\u00edctimas inocentes. Expresamos nuestras m\u00e1s sentidas palabras de condolencia y reivindicamos el derecho de todo ser humano a profesar libremente su religi\u00f3n.|first=Juan|last=Guaid\u00f3|date=21 April 2019|accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> and Vietnam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sggpnews.org.vn/national/vietnamese-leaders-send-condolences-after-bomb-attacks-in-sri-lanka-81467.html |title=Vietnamese leaders send condolences after bomb attacks in Sri Lanka |author1=Thanh Nam |author2=Huyen Huong |publisher=[[S\u00e0i G\u00f2n Gi\u1ea3i Ph\u00f3ng]] |date=22 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref>|name=|group=}} [[President of the European Parliament]] [[Antonio Tajani]] referred to the bombings as an act of genocide.<ref name=\"Tajani Tweet\">{{cite web |last1=Tajani |first1=Antonio |title=Even on Easter Sunday, there are those who sow hatred and reap death. The attacks in #SriLanka churches testify to a real genocide perpetrated against Christians. Let us pray for the innocent victims and work towards religious freedom around the world. |url=https://twitter.com/EP_President/status/1119871493637324800 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190429230640/https://twitter.com/EP_President/status/1119871493637324800 |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 April 2019 |website=Twitter |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Factbox: Reaction to Sri Lanka attacks |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-sri-lanka-blasts-reaction-factbox/factbox-reaction-to-sri-lanka-attacks-idUKKCN1RX09G?feedType=RSS&feedName=worldNews |website=REUTERS}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Finlandia Hall illuminated 2019-04-23.jpg|thumb|The [[Finlandia Hall]] in [[Helsinki]] illuminated in the colours of the [[Sri Lankan flag]] to express solidarity]]\nAfter the bombings, numerous buildings around the world were illuminated in Sri Lanka's colours, some of which included the [[Flinders Street railway station]] in [[Melbourne]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fowler|first1=Michael|last2=Mills|first2=Tammy|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/united-we-stand-melbourne-s-sri-lankan-community-gathers-to-pay-respects-20190422-p51g83.html|title='United we stand': Melbourne's Sri Lankan community gathers to pay respects|publisher=The Age|date=22 April 2019|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> the [[Sydney Opera House|Opera House]] in [[Sydney]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Quested |first1=Victoria |title=Sydney Opera House Lights Up in Support of Sri Lanka |url=https://10daily.com.au/news/australia/a190424agvjs/sydney-opera-house-to-light-up-in-support-of-sri-lanka-20190424 |accessdate=25 April 2019 |work=10 daily |date=24 April 2019 |language=en-AU}}</ref> the [[Victoria Bridge, Brisbane|Victoria Bridge]] in [[Brisbane]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.facebook.com/abcinbrisbane/posts/victoria-bridge-is-lit-up-green-orange-crimson-and-yellow-the-colors-of-the-flag/10157350974459669/|title= Victoria bridge is lit up green, orange, chrome on and yellow|publisher= ABC Brisbane|date=22 April 2019|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> the [[Finlandia Hall]] in [[Helsinki]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsnowfinland.fi/finland-international/finlandia-hall-lights-up-for-sri-lanka-victims|title=Finlandia Hall lights up for Sri Lanka victims|publisher=News Now Finland|date=23 April 2019|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> the [[Northern Spire Bridge]] and [[Penshaw Monument]] in [[Sunderland]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Kirby|first=Sue|url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/people/sunderland-landmarks-to-be-lit-up-as-a-mark-of-solidarity-with-sri-lanka-1-9730128|title=Sunderland landmarks to be lit up as a mark of solidarity with Sri Lanka|publisher=Sunderland Echo|date=24 April 2019|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> the [[Burj Khalifa]] in [[Dubai]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/nation/dubai/dubais-burj-khalifa-lights-up-with-sri-lanka-flag-12|title=Dubai's Burj Khalifa lights up with Sri Lanka flag|work=Khaleej Times|date=26 April 2019|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref> the [[Emirates Palace]], [[ADNOC Headquarters]], [[Capital Gate]] and [[Marina Mall, Abu Dhabi|Marina Mall]] in [[Abu Dhabi]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Al Serkal |first1=Mariam M. |title=Look: UAE buildings light up in solidarity with Sri Lanka |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/look-uae-buildings-light-up-in-solidarity-with-sri-lanka-1.1556171492101 |accessdate=2 May 2019 |work=Gulf News |date=25 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> the [[Tel Aviv City Hall|City Hall]] in [[Tel Aviv]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Tel Aviv City Hall lights up with Sri Lanka flag |url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Tel-Aviv-city-hall-lights-up-with-Sri-Lanka-flag-587524 |accessdate=2 May 2019 |work=The Jerusalem Post |date=22 April 2019}}</ref> the [[Pennsylvania State Capitol]] in [[Harrisburg]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Murphy|first=Jan|url=https://www.pennlive.com/news/2019/04/pa-capitol-to-be-lit-in-orange-and-green-to-honor-victims-of-sri-lanka-bombings.html|title=Pa. Capitol to be lit in orange and green to honor victims of Sri Lanka bombings|publisher=PennLive|date=22 April 2019|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> and the [[Sky Tower (Auckland)|Sky Tower]] in [[Auckland]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lawton|first=Nicole|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/112290971/sky-tower-to-glow-in-colours-of-the-sri-lankan-flag-to-remember-bombing-victims|title=Sky Tower to glow in colours of the Sri Lankan flag to remember bombing victims|website=Stuff.co.nz|date=26 April 2019|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref> The [[Eiffel Tower]] in Paris went dark as a memorial for the victims of the bombings.<ref>{{cite news|last=Waldrop|first=Theresa|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/21/europe/eiffel-tower-lights-off-sri-lanka/index.html|title=Eiffel Tower goes dark to honor Sri Lanka attack victims|publisher=CNN|date=21 April 2019|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[New York Stock Exchange]] paused for a moment of silence before the opening bell on the day after the attacks.<ref name=\"Insider\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisinsider.com/sri-lanka-bombings-vigils-tributes-photos-details-2019-4#traders-at-the-new-york-stock-exchange-paused-for-a-moment-of-silence-before-the-opening-bell-on-monday-3| title=People around the world are honoring the victims of the Sri Lanka bombings that killed more than 300 people|date=23 April 2019|website=INSIDER|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref> [[Real Madrid C.F.]] also had a moment of silence before the [[La Liga]] match on the night of the attacks.<ref name=\"Insider\" /> Candlelight vigils were held and flags were also flown at half-mast around the world including in Pakistan, Canada, Indonesia, New Zealand, Australia and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"Insider\" />\n\n=== Religious leaders ===\nRepresentatives and leaders of the main world religions responded with prayers and support for the victims.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sri-lanka-blasts-reaction-factbox-idUSKCN1RX09I|title=Factbox: Reaction to Sri Lanka attacks|date=22 April 2019|publisher= Reuters |accessdate= 24 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Pope Francis]] pledged his closeness and solidarity after the attacks during his ''[[Urbi et Orbi]]'' address in [[St. Peter's Square]].<ref name=\"VaticanNewsWatkins2019\" /> The following day, he urged the international community to help Sri Lanka, and called on them to condemn terrorist acts.<ref name=\"VaticanNewsGomes2019\">{{cite news |last1=Gomes |first1=Robin |title=Pope Francis, Asian Bishops, others renew solidarity with Sri Lanka after blasts |url=https://www.vaticannews.va/en/pope/news/2019-04/pope-francis-sri-lanka-terrorist-attacks-asia-bishops-bo-gracias.html |accessdate=2 May 2019 |work=Vatican News |date=22 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]], a 57-member state international body, strongly condemned the terrorist acts, and called for international solidarity in the fight against terrorism.<ref>{{cite web |title=OIC Secretary General Strongly Condemned the Terrorist Attacks in Sri Lanka |url=https://www.oic-oci.org/topic/?t_id=20831&ref=11796&lan=en |website=[[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]] |accessdate=6 June 2019 |date=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nCardinal [[Charles Maung Bo]] of Myanmar, the President of the Federation of Asian Bishops' Conference (FABC) and Cardinal [[Oswald Gracias]] of India, the President of Catholic Bishops Conference of India (CBCI) also condemned the attacks.<ref name=\"VaticanNewsGomes2019\" />\n\nThe [[World Council of Churches]], an [[ecumenical]] body representing several major Christian traditions, expressed sentiments of solidarity with the Christians of Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"Adams2019\">{{cite web |last1= Adams |first1=David |title= Christian leaders condemn Sri Lankan terror attacks |url= https://www.sightmagazine.com.au/news/12033-christian-leaders-condemn-sri-lankan-terror-attacks | work = Sight Magazine |accessdate= 23 April 2019 |date= 22 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nCondolences for the those affected and condemnations of the attacks were variously offered by the leaders of [[Anglicanism|Anglican]],<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-asia-48002165 |title= Live: Attacks on Sri Lanks churches and hotels|website= BBC|date= 21 April 2019|accessdate= 21 April 2019 | quote = Archbishop of Canterbury: 'Despicable destruction'}}</ref> [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|Latter-day Saint]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mormonnewsroom.in/article/church-leaders-offer-words-of-sorrow-and-comfort-following-bombings-in-sri-lanka |title=Bombings in Sri Lanka|date=21 April 2019|website= Mormon news room |accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref> [[Methodism|Methodist]],<ref>{{cite web |title= WMC Statement on Easter Attacks in Sri Lanka |url= https://worldmethodistcouncil.org/statement-on-easter-attacks-in-sri-lanka/ |publisher=[[World Methodist Council]] |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox]],<ref>{{cite web|url= https://mospat.ru/en/2019/04/21/news173041/|title=Patriarch Kirill's condolences over the terrorist action in Sri Lanka |publisher= The Russian Orthodox Church|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://adevarul.ro/news/eveniment/patriarhul-daniel-despre-atacurilor-sri-lanka-expresia-cea-mai-cruda-violentei-instrainarii-dumnezeu-1_5cbc6f8a445219c57ecc4417/index.html |title=Patriarhul Daniel, despre atacurile din Sri Lanka: Expresia cea mai crud\u0103 a violen\u021bei \u0219i a \u00eenstr\u0103in\u0103rii de Dumnezeu |work= Adev\u0103rul |date=21 April 2019 |language= Romanian}}</ref> [[Evangelicalism|Evangelical]],<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.worldea.org/news/4934/wea-condemns-coward-bombings-mourns-lives-lost-in-easter-sunday-attacks-in-sri-lanka|title=WEA Condemns Coward Bombings, Mourns Lives Lost in Easter Sunday Attacks in Sri Lanka |website= World EA|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> and [[Calvinism|Reformed]] churches,<ref>{{cite web |last1= Williams |first1= Alex |title=Sri Lankan minister says Easter Sunday attacks are 'retaliation for Christchurch mosque shooting' |url= https://www.premier.org.uk/News/World/Sri-Lankan-minister-says-Easter-Sunday-attacks-are-retaliation-for-Christchurch-mosque-shooting |publisher= [[Premier Christian Radio|Premier]] |accessdate=24 April 2019 |date= 23 April 2019}}</ref> as well as Muslim<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.muis.gov.sg/Media/Media-Releases/21-Apr-19-Muis-Statement-Against-Multiple-Bombings-in-Sri-Lanka|title=MUIS' STATEMENT AGAINST MULTIPLE BOMBINGS IN SRI LANKA|website=www.muis.gov.sg|access-date=5 May 2019}}</ref> and [[Judaism|Jewish]] congregations.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[All Ceylon Jamiyyathul Ulama]], a council of Muslim theologians, sent condolences.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/south-asia/sri-lanka-muslim-leaders-call-for-maximum-punishment-for-suicide-strikes |title= Sri Lanka explosions: Local Muslim leaders call for 'maximum punishment' for culprits | via = [[Agence France-Presse]] |date=22 April 2019|website= [[The Straits Times]] |publisher= Singapore Press Holdings |access-date=24 April 2019}}</ref> Several theologians met with [[Malcolm Ranjith]], the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Colombo|Archbishop of Colombo]], following the attacks. The National Shoora Council, composed of eighteen Muslim organisations, also expressed condolences.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 28 May 2019, a mosque belonging to the NTJ was intentionally destroyed by the Muslim civilians in the [[Kekirawa]] community, which included the chief of a neighbouring mosque. The structure was purportedly built using foreign funds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Muslims demolish NTJ mosque in Kekirawa |url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news.php?nid=55442 |accessdate=31 May 2019 |publisher=[[Ada Derana]] |date=30 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ariyadasa |first1=Kanchana Kumara |title=NTJ mosque in Kekirawa demolished by Muslims |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/NTJ-mosque-in-Kekirawa-demolished-by-Muslims/108-168204 |accessdate=31 May 2019 |publisher=[[Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)|Daily Mirror]] |date=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[1971 JVP insurrection]], an armed revolt in Sri Lanka following the disbanding of the state intelligence agency.\n* [[List of terrorist incidents in April 2019]]\n* [[List of massacres in Sri Lanka]]\n* [[2019 anti-Muslim riots in Sri Lanka]]\n\n=== Similar ISIL attacks ===\n* [[2019 Jolo Cathedral bombings]]\n* [[2017 Quetta church attack]]\n* [[July 2016 Dhaka attack]]\n* [[Palm Sunday church bombings]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://roar.media/english/life/in-the-know/easter-sunday-explosions-in-sri-lanka/ Timeline of events, ''Roar Media'']\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2019/apr/21/sri-lanka-explosions-dozens-killed-and-hundreds-injured-in-church-and-hotel-blasts Timeline of events, ''The Guardian'']\n\n{{2019 Sri Lanka Easter bombings}}\n{{Persecution of Christians}}\n{{2019 in Sri Lanka}}\n{{Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}}\n{{Portal bar|Christianity|Islam|Sri Lanka}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019 Sri Lanka Easter bombings}}\n[[Category:2019 Sri Lanka Easter bombings| ]]\n[[Category:2019 in Christianity]]\n[[Category:2010s murders in Sri Lanka|2019 Easter bombings]]\n[[Category:21st century in Colombo]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in Sri Lanka|2019 Easter bombings]]\n[[Category:Anti-Christian sentiment in Asia]]\n[[Category:April 2019 crimes in Asia]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2019]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in Sri Lanka|2019 Easter bombings]]\n[[Category:Attacks on churches in Asia]]\n[[Category:Attacks on hotels in Asia]]\n[[Category:Attacks on tourists in Asia]]\n[[Category:Batticaloa]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Sri Lanka|2019 Easter bombings]]\n[[Category:Civilian 